{"title_page": "Jamesville-DeWitt High School", "text_new": "{{Infobox school\n|name= Jamesville-DeWitt High School\n|image_name=Jamesville-DeWitt High School (new gym).jpg\n|image_size =\n|established=\n|endowment =\n|motto =\n|faculty=\n|principal= Paul Gasparini\n|students=\n|district = [[Jamesville-DeWitt Central School District]]\n|streetaddress=6845 Edinger Drive\n|city= [[Dewitt, New York|DeWitt]]\n|state= [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|zipcode=13214-0606\n|country= [[United States]]\n|coordinates={{coord|43.019411|-76.045496|type:edu_region:US-NY|display=title,inline|format=dms}}\n|campus=\n|ratio=13.53<ref name=NCES/>\n|staff=70.02 (FTE)<ref name=NCES/>\n|enrollment=947 (2017\u201318)<ref name=NCES>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=3609090&ID=360909000697|title=JAMESVILLE-DEWITT HIGH SCHOOL|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n|conference=[[Onondaga High School League]]\n|newspaper=The Rampage\n|free_label=\n|free=\n|nickname =\n|mascot= Red Ram\n|colors= Green and white {{Color box|Green|border=darkgray}}{{Color box|white|border=darkgray}}\n|website= [http://www.jamesvilledewitt.org/teacherpage.cfm?teacher=331 School website]\n}}\n\n'''Jamesville-DeWitt High School''' (JDHS) is a [[New York (state)|New York]] state public education facility located in the town of [[DeWitt, New York|DeWitt]], serving high school students (grades 9\u201312) in the [[Jamesville-Dewitt Central School District]]. The current principal is Paul Gasparini.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n[[File:Jamesville-DeWitt High School (main entrance).jpg|thumb|300px|Near the main entrance]]\n\n* [[Mark Dindal]] ('78): animator, movie director (Disney's ''[[The Emperor's New Groove]]'')\n* [[Robert Drummond (gridiron football)|Robert Drummond]] ('85): former [[NFL]] and [[Syracuse University Orange]] player \n* [[Jon Fishman]] ('83): [[Phish]] drummer\n* [[Eliot Fisk]] ('72): classical guitarist\n* [[Andy Rautins]] ('05): current [[Tulsa 66ers]] guard and former [[Syracuse Orange basketball]] player \n* [[Mike Royce]] ('82): comedian\n* [[Danny Schayes]] ('77): [[NBA]] player\n* [[Scott Schwedes]] ('83): former [[NFL]] and [[Syracuse University Orange]] player \n* [[Suzy Whaley]] ('84): [[LPGA]] golfer; in 2003 became the first woman to qualify for a [[PGA Tour]] event\n* [[Tyler Cavanaugh]] ('11): Professional [[NBA]] basketball player for [[Atlanta Hawks]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.jamesvilledewitt.org/ Jamesville-DeWitt web page]\n* {{Commons cat inline|Jamesville-DeWitt High School}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jamesville-Dewitt High School}}\n[[Category:Public high schools in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Schools in Onondaga County, New York]]\n[[Category:DeWitt, New York]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox school\n|name= Jamesville-DeWitt High School\n|image_name=Jamesville-DeWitt High School (new gym).jpg\n|image_size =\n|established=\n|endowment =\n|motto =\n|faculty=\n|principal= Paul Gasparini\n|students=\n|district = [[Jamesville-DeWitt Central School District]]\n|streetaddress=6845 Edinger Drive\n|city= [[Dewitt, New York|DeWitt]]\n|state= [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|zipcode=13214-0606\n|country= [[United States]]\n|coordinates={{coord|43.019411|-76.045496|type:edu_region:US-NY|display=title,inline|format=dms}}\n|campus=\n|ratio=13.53<ref name=NCES/>\n|staff=70.02 (FTE)<ref name=NCES/>\n|enrollment=947 (2017\u201318)<ref name=NCES>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=3609090&ID=360909000697|title=JAMESVILLE-DEWITT HIGH SCHOOL|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n|conference=[[Onondaga High School League]]\n|newspaper=The Rampage\n|free_label=\n|free=\n|nickname =\n|mascot= Red Ram\n|colors= Red and white {{Color box|red|border=darkgray}}{{Color box|white|border=darkgray}}\n|website= [http://www.jamesvilledewitt.org/teacherpage.cfm?teacher=331 School website]\n}}\n\n'''Jamesville-DeWitt High School''' (JDHS) is a [[New York (state)|New York]] state public education facility located in the town of [[DeWitt, New York|DeWitt]], serving high school students (grades 9\u201312) in the [[Jamesville-Dewitt Central School District]]. The current principal is Paul Gasparini.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n[[File:Jamesville-DeWitt High School (main entrance).jpg|thumb|300px|Near the main entrance]]\n\n* [[Mark Dindal]] ('78): animator, movie director (Disney's ''[[The Emperor's New Groove]]'')\n* [[Robert Drummond (gridiron football)|Robert Drummond]] ('85): former [[NFL]] and [[Syracuse University Orange]] player \n* [[Jon Fishman]] ('83): [[Phish]] drummer\n* [[Eliot Fisk]] ('72): classical guitarist\n* [[Andy Rautins]] ('05): current [[Tulsa 66ers]] guard and former [[Syracuse Orange basketball]] player \n* [[Mike Royce]] ('82): comedian\n* [[Danny Schayes]] ('77): [[NBA]] player\n* [[Scott Schwedes]] ('83): former [[NFL]] and [[Syracuse University Orange]] player \n* [[Suzy Whaley]] ('84): [[LPGA]] golfer; in 2003 became the first woman to qualify for a [[PGA Tour]] event\n* [[Tyler Cavanaugh]] ('11): Professional [[NBA]] basketball player for [[Atlanta Hawks]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.jamesvilledewitt.org/ Jamesville-DeWitt web page]\n* {{Commons cat inline|Jamesville-DeWitt High School}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jamesville-Dewitt High School}}\n[[Category:Public high schools in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Schools in Onondaga County, New York]]\n[[Category:DeWitt, New York]]\n", "name_user": "Vibez21", "label": "safe", "comment": "wrong school colors", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jamesville-DeWitt_High_School"}
{"title_page": "Cannabis in Canada", "text_new": "{{Use Canadian English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Cannabis in Canada sidebar}}\n'''Cannabis in Canada''' is legal for both [[cannabis (drug)|recreational]] and [[Medical cannabis|medicinal]] purposes. Medicinal use of [[cannabis]] was legalized nationwide on 30 July 2001 under conditions outlined in the [[Marihuana for Medical Purposes Regulations]], later superseded by the Access to Cannabis for Medical Purposes Regulations,<ref name=\"Access to Cannabis for Medical Purposes Regulations (SOR/2016-230)\">{{cite web|url=http://laws.justice.gc.ca/eng/regulations/SOR-2016-230/ |title=Access to Cannabis for Medical Purposes Regulations |publisher=laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/ |accessdate=20 March 2017}}</ref> issued by [[Health Canada]] and seed, grain, and fibre production was permitted under licence by Health Canada.<ref name=\"Hemp Laws\">{{cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/health-canada/services/health-concerns/controlled-substances-precursor-chemicals/industrial-hemp/about-hemp-canada-hemp-industry/frequently-asked-questions.html|title=Industrial Hemp Regulation Program FAQ|date=November 2012|publisher=Health Canada|accessdate=30 October 2013}}</ref> The federal ''[[Cannabis Act]]'' came into effect on 17 October 2018 and made Canada the second country in the world, after [[Uruguay]], to formally legalize the cultivation, possession, acquisition and consumption of cannabis and its [[Cannabis (drug)#Preparations|by-products]].<!--Whereas decriminalization would simply remove laws restricting the use of cannabis products, as has been implemented in many countries, legalization allows for the taxation of legally produced cannabis--><ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/06/20/health/canada-legalizes-marijuana/index.html|title=Canada becomes second nation in the world to legalize marijuana|last=Sapra|first=Bani|date=20 June 2018|work=[[CNN]]|access-date=}}</ref> Canada is the first [[G7]] and [[G20]] nation to do so.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jun/06/all-eyes-on-canada-as-first-g7-nation-prepares-to-make-marijuana-legal|title=All eyes on Canada as first G7 nation prepares to make marijuana legal|last=Ross|first=Selena|date=6 June 2018|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nCannabis was banned in Canada from 1923 until regulated medical cannabis became legal on 30 July 2001. In response to popular opinion,<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/2995390/canada-will-see-900000-new-pot-smokers-under-legalization-poll-implies/|title=Canada will see 900,000 new pot smokers under legalization, poll implies|last=Cain|first=Patrick|date=12 October 2016|work=[[Global News]]|access-date=4 February 2017}}</ref> the legislation to legalize cannabis for recreational use (''[[Cannabis Act]]'', Bill C-45) was passed by the [[House of Commons of Canada]] on 27 November 2017; it passed second reading in the [[Senate of Canada]] on 22 March 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nationalpost.com/cannabis/cp-newsalert-senate-backs-bill-to-legalize-recreational-marijuana|title=Bill to legalize marijuana passes second reading in Senate as Conservatives drop threat to block it|last=Vaughan|first=Andrew|date=23 March 2018|work=[[National Post]]|accessdate=23 June 2018|agency=[[The Canadian Press]]}}</ref> On 18 June 2018, the House passed the bill with most, but not all, of the Senate's amendments.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/policy/international/392846-canadas-house-of-commons-votes-to-legalize-marijuana|title=Canada's House of Commons votes to legalize marijuana|last=Anapol|first=Avery|date=18 June 2018|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|access-date=19 June 2018}}</ref> The Senate accepted this version of the Act the following day.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4282677/pot-bill-senate-passes/|title=Marijuana legalization Bill C-45 officially passes Senate vote, heading for royal assent|last=Scotti|first=Monique|date=19 June 2018|work=[[Global News]]}}</ref>\n\nThe federal government announced that recreational use of cannabis would no longer violate criminal law as of 17 October 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/cannabis-pot-legalization-bill-1.4713839|title=Trudeau says pot will be legal as of Oct. 17, 2018|last=Tasker|first=John Paul|date=20 June 2018|work=[[CBC News]]|access-date=}}</ref> This legalization comes with regulation similar to that of [[Alcoholic drinks in Canada|alcohol in Canada]], limiting home production, distribution, consumption areas and sale times.<ref name=\"Justice\">{{cite web |title=Cannabis Act (S.C. 2018, c. 16) |url=https://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/C-24.5/index.html |website=Justice Canada |publisher=Government of Canada |accessdate=24 November 2018}}</ref> The process removed cannabis possession for personal consumption from the [[Controlled Drugs and Substances Act]]; while implementing taxation and strengthen punishment of those convicted of either supplying cannabis to minors, or of impairment while driving a motor vehicle.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/tax-on-legalized-pot-won-t-be-a-cash-cow-pm-1.2704748|title=Tax on legalized pot won't be a cash cow: PM|last=Bronskill|first=Jim|date=17 December 2015|work=[[CTV News]]|access-date=23 December 2015|agency=[[The Canadian Press]]}}</ref>\n\nAs of January 2019, on-line sales of cannabis for recreational use were well underway across Canada, via the provincial or territorial governments. Most provinces also had storefront operations selling cannabis, either operated by the government or private enterprise. The number of retailers is likely to remain limited, largely due to insufficient supply of legal cannabis from licensed producers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/cannabis/2019/01/10/ontario-is-holding-a-lottery-for-cannabis-stores-on-friday-heres-what-the-rest-of-the-country-tried-and-how-it-turned-out.html|title=Ontario is holding a lottery for cannabis stores on Friday. Here's what the rest of the country tried and how it turned out|date=10 January 2019 |work=Toronto Star|accessdate=11 January 2019\n}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{main|Legal history of cannabis in Canada}}\n[[File:BlackCandle.jpg|thumb|200px|The cover of Murphy's 1922 book ''The Black Candle'', that claimed \"marijuana turned its users into homicidal maniacs.\"<ref name=\"BrunoCsiernik2018\">{{cite book|author1=Tara L. Bruno|author2=Rick Csiernik|title=The Drug Paradox: An Introduction to the Sociology of Psychoactive Substances in Canada|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hbpaDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA21|year=2018|publisher=Canadian Scholars|isbn=978-1-77338-052-0|page=21}}</ref>]]\nDrug prohibition in Canada began with the Opium Act of 1908.<ref name=\"McCormickMcCormick2005\">{{cite book|author1=Christopher Ray McCormick|author2=Chris McCormick|author3=Len Green|title=Crime and Deviance in Canada: Historical Perspectives|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NcVZPgwoNvoC&pg=PA355|year=2005|publisher=Canadian Scholars' Press|isbn=978-1-55130-274-4|page=355}}</ref> Historians often point to the 1922 publication of [[Emily Murphy]]'s ''The Black Candle''  as the catalyst for the addition of the three extra drugs to a list of prohibited substances.<ref name=\"Lee2012\">{{cite book|author=Martin A. Lee|title=Smoke Signals: A Social History of Marijuana \u2013 Medical, Recreational and Scientific|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n-SG3oWUjhMC&pg=PA325|date=14 August 2012|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4391-0260-2|pages=325}}</ref> Murphy's anti-drug screeds were widely read and helped spread the drug panic across the country, historian Catharine Carstairs disputes that the seven-page chapter, \"Marahuana -- a new menace\" inspired the inclusion of cannabis as a restricted substance.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/obj/s4/f2/dsk4/etd/MQ81078.pdf |title=The Grandmother of Marijuana Prohibition |last=House |first=Yolande |date=May 2003 |website=Collections Canada |publisher=Government of Canada |access-date=18 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/health/marijuana-was-criminalized-in-1923-but-why-1.2630436|title=A Canadian mystery: Why was pot criminalized in 1923? |publisher=- CBC News}}</ref>\n\nCannabis was made illegal when it was added to the country's Confidential Restricted List in 1923 under the ''Narcotics Drug Act Amendment Bill'' after a vague reference to a \"new drug\" during a late night session of the House of Commons on 23 April 1923.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/health/marijuana-was-criminalized-in-1923-but-why-1.2630436|title=Marijuana was criminalized in 1923, but why?|last=Daniel|first=Schartz|date=3 May 2014|work=[[CBC News]]|accessdate=29 July 2014|quote=The only mention of the proposed changes to the schedule recorded in Hansard was on 23 April, when Beland told the House of Commons, \"There is a new drug in the schedule.\"}}</ref> According to one government official, cannabis was outlawed after the Director of the Federal Division of Narcotic Control returned from [[League of Nations]] meetings where the international control of cannabis was broached.<ref name=\"Carstairs\">{{cite journal|last=Carstairs|first=Catherine|year=2000|title='Hop Heads' and 'Hypes': Drug Use, Regulation and Resistance in Canada, 1920\u20131961|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/obj/s4/f2/dsk2/ftp03/NQ53757.pdf|version=PhD dissertation|publisher=University of Toronto|accessdate=2 January 2008}}</ref>{{rp|49}} Cannabis did not begin to attract official attention in Canada until the later 1930s, and even then it was minimal.<ref name=\"Carstairs\" />{{rp|51}} The first seizure of cannabis by Canadian police was not made until 1937.<ref name=\"Carstairs\" />{{rp|48}} Commercial cultivation of [[industrial hemp]] was forbidden in 1938.<ref>{{cite book|title=Textile Horizons|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8uPxAAAAMAAJ|year=2005|publisher=ITBD|page=119}}</ref> Between 1946 and 1961, cannabis accounted for only 2% of all drug arrests in Canada.<ref name=\"Carstairs\" />{{rp|112}}\n\nIn the 1960s, cannabis arrests began to increase rapidly in Canada. For the entire period of 1930\u20131946, the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police|RCMP]] recorded only 25 cannabis arrests, but this rose to 2,300 cases in 1968, and to 12,000 cases in 1972.<ref name=\"DrugsKenny2003\">{{cite book|author1=Canada. Parliament. Senate. Special Committee on Illegal Drugs|author2=Colin Kenny|author3=Pierre Claude Nolin|title=Cannabis: Report of the Senate Special Committee on Illegal Drugs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L_5gu-eUfE8C&pg=PA59|year=2003|publisher=University of Toronto Press|isbn=978-0-8020-8630-3|pages=59}}</ref> In response to the increased popularization of marijuana and the increase in criminal charges against middle class citizens, the government formed the Royal Commission of Inquiry into the Non-Medical Use of Drugs, usually referred to as the [[Le Dain Commission]], in 1969 to investigate non-medical cannabis use in Canada.<ref name=\"RutherdaleFahrni2008\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8uKz-8jB4WsC&pg=PA318|title=Creating Postwar Canada: Community, Diversity, and Dissent, 1945\u201375|date=1 July 2008|publisher=[[UBC Press]]|isbn=978-0-7748-5815-1|editor-last=Rutherdale|editor-first=Robert|pages=318\u2013|editor-last2=Fahrni|editor-first2=Magda}}</ref> The commission's 1972 report recommended removing criminal penalties for cannabis possession, though not legalization, per se. While the subsequent two federal governments discussed the recommendation, no steps were actually taken to change legislation.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hathaway|first=Andrew D.|date=2009|title=The Legal History and Cultural Experience of Cannabis|url=http://www.heretohelp.bc.ca/sites/default/files/visions_cannabis.pdf|journal=Visions|volume=5|issue=4|pages=12\u201313|access-date=16 December 2016|quote=In Canada, the government rejected the Le Dain proposal to remove criminal penalties for cannabis possession.}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, the country started a medical marijuana program, managed by [[Health Canada]]. The program originally offered people access to home grown cannabis or sales directly from Health Canada. This was replaced with new regulations that set up a more traditional commercial sector for cannabis cultivation and distribution in 2013.<ref>{{cite news |title=A timeline of some significant events in the history of medical marijuana in Canada |url=https://london.ctvnews.ca/medicalmarijuana/a-timeline-of-some-significant-events-in-the-history-of-medical-marijuana-in-canada-1.3858860 |accessdate=13 November 2018 |work=The Canadian Press, CTV News-London |date=2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.leafly.com/news/canada/guide-to-canada-medical-marijuana-program|title=A Guide to Canada's Medical Marijuana Program {{!}} Leafly|date=28 June 2017|work=Leafly|access-date=12 November 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Steps to legalization ==\n{{See|Cannabis Act}}\nAfter he was elected Prime Minister in 2015, the first significant step that [[Justin Trudeau]] took was the creation of a federal-provincial-territorial task force to discuss a jointly suitable process for the legalization of cannabis possession for casual use. This Task Force on Marijuana Legalization and Regulation released a 106-page report to the public on 13 December 2016, with various recommendations. Those were provided for consideration by the federal and provincial governments, but they were not binding.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bnnbloomberg.ca/ottawa-to-release-task-force-report-on-marijuana-legalization-1.630354|title=Task force recommends setting 18 as minimum age for pot purchases|author=The Canadian Press<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=13 December 2016|website=BNN|publisher=Bell Media|access-date=13 December 2016|quote=recreational marijuana should not be sold in the same location as alcohol or tobacco}}</ref> Sales for recreational use were not to commence until 1 July 2018, at the earliest, based on legislation (Bill C-45, the ''Cannabis Act'') passed by the federal government in June 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ipolitics.ca/2017/11/27/house-passes-pot-legalization-bill-senate-wild-card/|title=House passes pot legalization bill \u2013 but Senate could be a 'wild card'|last=Duggan|first=Kyle|date=27 November 2017|website=iPolitics}}</ref>\n\nThe substance remains controlled: sold only at government licensed retailers, and grown only by licensed producers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2016/11/14/shoppers-drug-mart-right-spot-to-sell-medicinal-pot-poll.html|title=Shoppers Drug Mart right spot to sell medicinal pot: poll|last=Wright|first=Lisa|date=14 November 2016|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|access-date=4 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/2987372/how-will-legal-pot-be-sold-liquor-stores-are-most-likely-option/|title=How will legal pot be sold? Three things that might happen, and one that won't|last=Cain|first=Patrick|date=9 October 2016|work=[[Global News]]|access-date=1 December 2016}}</ref> During the federal election campaign, the Liberals had promised \"new, stronger laws\" against sales to minors, driving while impaired, and sales through channels not specifically authorized to do so.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/marijuana-advisory-panel-report-questions-1.3872633|title=8 burning questions about the coming federal pot report|last=Cullen|first=Catherine|date=30 November 2016|work=[[CBC News]]|access-date=30 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nUntil 17 October 2018, cannabis remained illegal (except with a physician's prescription, for medical purposes), as Trudeau reminded police forces across the country in late 2016. He insisted that they \"enforce the law\": criminally charge illegal storefront dispensaries. Trudeau also explained that the intent of the legislation is not to encourage recreational use of cannabis. The intent is \"to better protect our kids from the easy access they have right now to marijuana [and] to remove the criminal elements that were profiting from marijuana\", he told the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' on 2 December 2016.<ref name=\"Benzie\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/queenspark/2016/12/03/trudeau-urges-police-to-enforce-the-law-on-marijuana.html|title=Trudeau urges police to 'enforce the law' on marijuana|last=Benzie|first=Robert|date=3 December 2016|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|access-date=4 December 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Marc Emery and Jodie Emery.JPG|thumb|[[Marc Emery|Marc]] and [[Jodie Emery]], Canadian [[cannabis rights]] activists.]]\nPolice forces took the Prime Minister seriously, and in March 2017, raided five locations of the Cannabis Culture retailer in [[Toronto]], one in [[Vancouver]], and another in [[Hamilton, Ontario]]. They also searched homes in Toronto, [[Stoney Creek, Ontario|Stoney Creek]], and Vancouver. Multiple charges were laid against [[Marc Emery]] and [[Jodie Emery]], owners of [[Cannabis Culture (magazine)|Cannabis Culture]], a company that franchised pot dispensary shops. The couple was convicted in December 2017 of drug-related charges, including possession of marijuana for the purpose of trafficking; fined; and placed on two years of probation.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news|url=https://nationalpost.com/news/canada/pot-activists-marc-and-jodie-emery-plead-guilty-to-drug-related-charges|title=Pot activists Marc and Jodie Emery plead guilty to drug-related charges|last=Casey|first=Liam|date=18 December 2017|work=[[National Post]]|agency=[[The Canadian Press]]}}</ref> Drug-related charges were laid against three others who were also subsequently convicted.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n[[Toronto Police Service|Toronto Police]] had told the media that the unlicensed cannabis dispensaries are linked to \"high-level drug traffickers ... often tied to organized crime, given the amount of marijuana sold\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Brait |first=Ellen |date=10 March 2017 |title='Prince and Princess of Pot' released on bail |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2017/03/09/prince-and-princess-of-pot-reportedly-arrested-at-toronto-airport.html | work=Toronto Star |location=Toronto |access-date=13 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[First Nations]] chiefs attending the [[Assembly of First Nations]] widely agreed that the distribution of cannabis on [[List of Indian reserves in Canada|reserve lands]] should be governed by First Nations governments, and not provincial legislation.<ref>{{cite news |title=First Nations demand control over cannabis sales |newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]] |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/first-nations-want-to-set-own-rules-for-cannabis-sales/article37231232/ |first=Gloria |last=Galloway |date=7 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nImmediately after legalization, licensed growers often had difficulty accessing financial services. [[Alterna Savings]] and [[Alterna Bank]] were among the first financial institutions to make loans to businesses focusing on cannabis in Canada, providing primary banking services for approximately two-thirds of the hundred licensed growers in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Alexander |first1=Doug |title=Alterna CEO embraced weed business when nobody else would |url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2018/04/06/alterna-ceo-embraced-weed-business-when-nobody-else-would.html |accessdate=2 May 2019 |work=Toronto Star |date=6 April 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Final legalization===\n{{see|An Act to amend the Criminal Code (offences relating to conveyances)}}\n[[File:Canadian_House_of_Commons_-_Bill_C-45_(Cannabis_Act)_-_Voting_Results_by_MP_(Simple_Map).svg|thumb|250px|Map showing which MP's voted in favour (green), against (red), abstained (grey) or whether the seat was vacant (black).]]\n\nAfter the House of Commons passed Bill C-45, it was sent to the Senate. On 1 June 2018, the Senate passed an amendment to C-45 outlawing cannabis \"brand-stretching\". The amendment, which passed 34\u201328 in the Senate,<ref name=dnapvp /> would have outlawed the sale and display of cannabis-related merchandise once legalized.<ref name=\"dnapvp\">{{cite web|url=https://ipolitics.ca/2018/06/01/senate-votes-to-ban-company-branded-cannabis-swag/|title=Senate votes to ban company branded cannabis swag|last=Duggan|first=Kyle|date=1 June 2018|website=iPolitics}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/marijuana-bill-faces-critical-vote-at-last-step-ahead-of-legalization-1.3958662|title=Timeline of key events in marijuana bill's passage through Parliament|last=Aiello|first=Rachel|date=4 June 2018|work=[[CTV News]]}}</ref> The amendment was rejected by the House of Commons.<ref>{{cite web |title=Motions Respecting Senate Amendments to Bills |publisher=[[Parliament of Canada]] |url=http://www.ourcommons.ca/DocumentViewer/en/42-1/house/sitting-316/order-notice/page-13 |date=18 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 June 2018, the Senate finally passed the bill, without the rejected amendment, and the Prime Minister announced the effective legalization date as 17 October 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4285946/marijuana-legal-date-october-17-canada-trudeau-confirms/|title=Marijuana to be legal in Canada starting October 17, Trudeau confirms|last=Scott|first=Monique|date=20 June 2018|work=[[Global News]]|access-date=}}</ref> Canada became the second nation (after [[Uruguay]]) to legalize the drug.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\nAs expected, the use of cannabis for recreational purposes became legal across the country on 17 October 2018, under the ''Cannabis Act'' which \"creates a legal and regulatory framework for controlling the production, distribution, sale and possession of cannabis in Canada\", according to a Government of Canada web site.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.canada.ca/en/health-canada/news/2018/06/backgrounder-the-cannabis-act-the-facts.html |title=The Cannabis Act: The Facts |date=20 June 2018 |website=Health Canada |publisher=Government of Canada |access-date=27 October 2018}}</ref> Persons aged 18 or older can possess up to 30 grams of dried or \"equivalent non-dried form\" in public. Adults are also allowed to make cannabis-infused food and drinks \"as long as organic solvents are not used to create concentrated products\". Each household is allowed to grow up to four cannabis plants from \"licensed seed or seedlings\", although Quebec and Manitoba chose to be excluded from this aspect of the legislation.\n\nEach province set its own procedures for retail sales, and these vary as to ownership or retail outlets (by the provincial government or private enterprise), but all include an option for on-line sales. Since marijuana is illegal in the U.S. per federal legislation, the government warned that \"previous use of cannabis, or any substance prohibited by U.S. federal laws, could mean that you are denied entry to the U.S.\" Canadians travelling within the country (but not internationally) are allowed to carry up to 30 grams of cannabis. Naturally, driving under the influence of drugs remained illegal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4559085/marijuana-legalization-canada-midnight/ |title=Marijuana is legal everywhere across Canada now |date=17 October 2018 |website=Inside Halton |publisher=Metroland News |access-date=27 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/marijuana-faq-legalization-need-to-know-1.4862207 |title=Cannabis is legal in Canada \u2013 here's what you need to know |date=17 October 2018 |website=CBC News |publisher=CBC |access-date=27 October 2018}}</ref> It was announced that on 1 May 2019, Canada would introduce excise tax on all products containing THC, and introduce three new product classes for recreational sale: cannabis edibles, cannabis extracts, and cannabis topicals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://extractmag.com/cannabis-edibles-extracts-and-topicals-thc-excise-tax-coming-to-canadians-may-1-2019/ |title=Cannabis Edibles, Extracts and Topicals & THC Excise Tax Coming To Canadians May 1, 2019 |date=19 March 2019 |website=Extract Magazine |publisher=Jordan Alexander |access-date=26 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs of August 2019, the federal government still prohibited the sale of edibles, such as cookies. Such products were expected to become legal in October 2019, but with restrictions. The intent was to not allow any products that would be \"appealing to young persons\", probably including the colourful \"gummies\" candy which was very popular on the black market.<ref>https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/companies-push-ahead-pot-gummy-plans-hazy-regulations-1.5259374, Companies push ahead on pot gummy plans despite hazy regulations</ref>\n\n== Public opinion, 1997\u20132016 ==\n[[File:Canada - Cannabis Day, Marijuana Party 2014 @ Art Gallery (14370054340).jpg|right|thumb|\"Canada/Cannabis Day\", 2014]]\nSince 1997, public opinion polls have found an increasing majority of Canadians agree with the statement, \"Smoking marijuana should not be a criminal offence\".<ref name=\"The Fraser Institute 1997\">{{cite web|url=http://oldfraser.lexi.net/publications/books/drug_papers/UDSavas.pdf|title=Public Opinion and Illicit Drugs \u2013 Canadian Attitudes towards Decriminalizing the Use of Marijuana|publisher=The Fraser Institute|date=April 2001|accessdate=23 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130629082437/http://oldfraser.lexi.net/publications/books/drug_papers/UDSavas.pdf|archive-date=29 June 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> In June 2016, a national poll conducted by [[Nanos Research]] showed that 7 in 10 Canadians were in favour of legalization.<ref name=\"Nanos Poll 2016\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/7-in-10-canadians-support-marijuana-legalization-nanos-poll-1.2968953|title=7 in 10 Canadians support marijuana legalization: Nanos poll|last=Tahirali|first=Jesse|date=30 June 2016|work=[[CTV News]]|accessdate=11 October 2016}}</ref>\nvgvvgv'\n\n\nBy 2006, a high percentage of the population was using cannabis,<ref name=\"Martel2006\">{{cite book|author=Marcel Martel|title=Not This Time: Canadians, Public Policy, and the Marijuana Question, 1961\u20131975|url=https://archive.org/details/notthistimecanad0000mart|url-access=registration|year=2006|publisher=University of Toronto Press, Scholarly Publishing Division|isbn=978-1-4426-5885-1|page=[https://archive.org/details/notthistimecanad0000mart/page/28 28]}}</ref> in spite of the risk of police charges for possession, and especially for selling it without the required licence, according to statistics gathered by the [[Centre for Addiction and Mental Health]] (CAMH). Nearly half (44%) of Canadians admit to trying it at least once; no statistics were provided as to the percentage who use it frequently. The CAMH report also indicates that by the last year of high school, nearly half (46%) of Ontario students admit to having used marijuana in the past year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.camh.ca/en/hospital/health_information/a_z_mental_health_and_addiction_information/marijuana/Pages/about_marijuana.aspx |title=About Marijuana |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2012 |website=CAMH |publisher=CAMH |access-date=2 December 2016}}</ref> The CAMH discussion includes warnings about the negative [[effects of cannabis]]. Other groups also warn about the risk, including the [[Canadian Automobile Association]] whose 2016 poll indicated, \"Almost two-thirds of Canadians are concerned that roads will become more dangerous [due to impairment by the drug] with the legalization of marijuana\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bcaa.com/learning-centre/bcaa-newsroom/news-releases/2016-11-14-caa-media-release-roads-unsafe-marijuana-legalized |title=Canadians Worry Roads Will Be Unsafe When Marijuana Legalized |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=14 November 2016 |website=BCAA |publisher=BCAA |access-date=2 December 2016 |quote=There are a lot of misconceptions out there that marijuana doesn't affect your driving, or even worse, it makes you a better driver ... There needs to be significant resources devoted to educating the public in the run-up to \u2013 and after \u2013 marijuana is legalized.}}</ref> An October 2016 national poll by Forum suggests that about five million adult Canadians now use cannabis at least once a month; this is expected to increase by 19 percent after marijuana is legalized.<ref name=\":2\" /> [[Canaccord Genuity]] analysts Matt Bottomley and Neil Maruoka released a research note with a more moderate estimate of the number of users. They predicted that approximately 3.8 million persons will be recreational users (presumably on a frequent basis) by 2021.<ref name=\"Skerrit\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/investment-ideas/marijuana-producer-jumps-356-in-canadas-investor-pot-frenzy/article33100749/|title=Marijuana producer jumps 356% as Canada's investor pot frenzy intensifies|last=Skerrit|first=Jen|date=30 November 2016|newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]]|access-date=2 December 2016|agency=[[Bloomberg News]]|last2=Lam|first2=Eric}}</ref> A report by Canada's [[Parliamentary Budget Officer]] (PBO) is more bullish, estimating that by 2021 some 5.2 million adults may be users.<ref name=\"Cullen\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/marijuana-parliamentary-budget-officer-revenues-1.3830593|title=Legal marijuana could raise federal cash \u2013 but not right away, PBO says|last=Cullen|first=Catherine|date=1 November 2016|work=[[CBC News]]|access-date=4 December 2016|quote=In the first three years, it expects the number of cannabis users aged 15 and over to grow by more than half a million, rising to an estimated 5.2 million in 2021.}}</ref>\n\n== Cannabis as a commodity ==\n[[File:Cannabis Indica 01.jpg|Example of a container and the recreational cannabis purchase in Canada.|thumb]] [[File:Emballage de cannabis Indica 03.jpg|Mandatory cannabis excise stamp on recreational cannabis sold in Canada.|thumb]]\nGrowers that currently produce marijuana are licensed by Health Canada under the [[Access to Cannabis for Medical Purposes Regulations (ACMPR).|Access to Cannabis for Medical Purposes Regulations]] (ACMPR). As of late 2016, there were 36 authorized producers across the country in Health Canada's list. Sales were allowed only by mail order, but by late 2017, some major retailers had applied for a change in the rules to allow them to also sell the product.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2017/11/13/shoppers-drug-mart-seeks-medical-marijuana-brand-manager.html|title=Shoppers Drug Mart seeks medical marijuana brand manager|last=Ligaya|first=Armina|date=13 November 2017|work=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref> By 21 December 2017, 82 licences had been issued<ref>{{cite news|url=https://business.financialpost.com/investing/marijuana-stocks-see-big-gains-as-trading-resumes-after-christmas-break|title=Marijuana stocks surge again as trading resumes after Christmas break|last=Zochodne|first=Geoff|date=27 December 2017|work=[[Financial Post]]}}</ref> under the ACMPR, but not all of the producers had been licensed to begin selling medical marijuana. The vast majority of these companies were located in Ontario.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/health-canada/services/drugs-health-products/medical-use-marijuana/licensed-producers/authorized-licensed-producers-medical-purposes.html|title=Authorized Licensed Producers of Cannabis for Medical Purposes \u2013 Canada.ca|first=Health|last=Canada|website=canada.ca}}</ref> At that time, no licences had been issued yet for producing recreational cannabis; the producers already licensed were hoping to be added to that list after it is created.<ref name=\"financialpost.com\">{{cite news|url=https://business.financialpost.com/investing/medical-marijuana-producers-bristle-at-ontarios-planned-monopoly-on-recreational-cannabis-sales|title=Medical marijuana producers bristle at Ontario's planned monopoly on recreational cannabis sales|last=Zochodne|first=Geoff|date=11 September 2017|work=[[Financial Post]]}}</ref> Between 1 February and early April 2018, some 89 additional applicants were approved as cannabis growers by Health Canada; at the time, the agency was considering the merits of another 244 applications.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-04-05/marijuana-millionaires-riding-canada-s-legalization-wave|title=Marijuana Millionaires Ride Canada's Legalization Wave|last=Skerritt|first=Jen|date=5 April 2018|work=[[Bloomberg News]]}}</ref>\n\nStatistics indicate that, as of September 2016, nearly 100,000 Canadians had bought medical marijuana legally, a significant increase over the 30,537 in September 2015, presumably since it is becoming a mainstream drug and since supplies are becoming more readily available.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/number-of-canadians-buying-legal-medical-marijuana-triples-in-just-one-year|title=Number of Canadians buying legal medical marijuana triples in just one year|last=Miller|first=Jacquie|date=12 December 2016|newspaper=[[Ottawa Citizen]]|access-date=14 December 2016}}</ref> According to a [[StatsCan]] estimate, Canadians may have spent roughly CAD$6.2 billion (US$4.8 billion) on marijuana in 2015, although the agency admits that there is no scientific method of accurately measuring illegal consumption.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloombergquint.com/business/2017/12/18/marijuana-use-may-have-hit-c-6-2-bln-before-canada-legalization|title=Canadians Consume Almost as Much Weed as Wine, Report Shows|last=Quinn|first=Greg|date=19 December 2017|work=[[BloombergQuint]]}}</ref>\n\nThe report by the Task Force on Marijuana Legalization and Regulation had recommended that recreational cannabis growers should be licensed at a federal level, separately from the producers of medical marijuana. The expert panel also recommended that the process ensure competition by licensing both large and small producers. While licensing should be federal, each of the provinces should be allowed to determine how and where the product will be sold.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://in.reuters.com/article/us-canada-marijuana-idINKBN1421UG|title=Canada should regulate recreational pot production: panel|last=Schnurr|first=Leah|date=13 December 2016|access-date=13 December 2016|agency=[[Reuters]]|last2=Ljunggren|first2=David|quote=The Canadian government should regulate the production of cannabis when it is legalized for recreational use while the provinces should be allowed to determine how it is sold, an official panel recommended on Tuesday.}}</ref>\n\nAfter the plans for legalization<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-12-20/trudeau-sees-pot-legalized-by-summer-as-law-sits-in-senate|title=Trudeau Sees Pot Legalized by Summer as Law Sits in Senate|last=Wingrove|first=Josh|date=20 December 2017|work=[[Bloomberg News]]}}</ref> became well-publicized, industry analysts reported that some of the producers who had been licensed for medical marijuana, including [[Aurora Cannabis]], were already increasing the capacity of their operations for future sales to the distributors of recreational cannabis.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/marijuana-businesses-legalization-date-1.4042599|title=Marijuana industry gets boost from legalization target date|last=Israel|first=Solomon|date=28 March 2017|work=[[CBC News]]|access-date=28 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nA report in late November 2017 by [[Ernst & Young]] suggested that there would be mergers, leaving fewer players in this industry. \"Many believe that consolidation is inevitable, leaving a few large players post-legalization.\" Also in late 2017, [[Deloitte]] predicted that the recreational cannabis market would be worth close to $23 billion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/marijuana-cannabis-mergers-pot-canada-1.4415933|title=Merger madness: Canada's marijuana industry enters consolidation phase|last=Armstrong|first=Peter|date=27 November 2017|work=[[CBC News]]}}</ref> Lately, US Alcohol companies have been showing interest in the Cannabis business in Canada.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/thomaspellechia/2018/09/13/canadas-cannabis-future-attracts-u-s-alcohol-companies/#5039255ec40c|title=Canada's Cannabis Future Attracts U.S. Alcohol Companies|last=Pellechia|first=Thomas|work=Forbes|access-date=30 September 2018|language=en}}</ref> US Cannabis producers are afraid that Canada is going to be the prime dominator in the market.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2018/09/29/canadian-cannabis-dominate-industry_a_23545796/|title=U.S. Cannabis Producers Fear Canada Will 'Dominate The Industry'|date=29 September 2018|work=HuffPost Canada|access-date=30 September 2018|language=en-CA}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 October 2019, alternative cannabis products such as drinks, edibles, and topicals will become legal for production,<ref>{{cite news |title=Cannabis edibles available for sale legally in mid-December|first=Hannah |last=Thibedeau |date=24 June 2019 |website=CBC News |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/marijuana-cannabis-edibles-extracts-vaping-1.5174844 |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref> and are expected to be available for sale two months later. [[Deloitte]] has predicted that the alternative cannabis product market will be worth close to $2.7 billion.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sokic |first1=Nicholas |title=Deloitte pegs market for alternative cannabis products at $2.7 billion |url=https://business.financialpost.com/cannabis/deloitte-pegs-market-for-alternative-cannabis-products-at-2-7-billion |work=Financial Post |date=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nDue to illegality of cannabis [[Cannabis in the United States|federally in the United States]], crossing the international border from Canada into the United States while carrying cannabis is still illegal. Past consumption of cannabis can also lead to a permanent ban on entry to the U.S.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tasker |first1=John Paul |title=Cannabis and the border: what pot-smoking Canadians need to know |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/tasker-smoke-pot-us-border-oct-17-1.4865696 |accessdate=3 March 2019 |work=CBC |date=16 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Major producers (2018)===\nAs of late October 2018, the largest of the producers licensed by the federal government was [[Canopy Growth Corporation]] of [[Smiths Falls, Ontario]]; the company was renamed from Tweed Marijuana Inc. in September 2015<ref>{{cite news|url=https://business.financialpost.com/news/agriculture/tweed-marijuana-renames-itself-canopy-growth-corp-as-it-charts-growth-path-at-agm|title=Tweed Marijuana renames itself Canopy Growth Corp as it charts growth path at AGM|last=Koven|first=Peter|date=17 September 2016|newspaper=[[Financial Post]]|access-date=2 December 2016}}</ref> after it purchased competitor Bedrocan. Subsequent acquisitions for this corporation included Vert Medical, the German cannabis distributor MedCann, and a majority interest in Quebec's Groupe H.E.M.P.CA Inc. In early December 2016, Canopy announced a friendly takeover bid of another Canadian producer, Mettrum Health (CVE:MT), in anticipation of an expanding market after marijuana is legalized for recreational purposes in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mettrum.com/investors/news-releases/canopy-growth-and-mettrum-announce-respective-shareholder-approvals-of-the-plan-of-arrangement/ |title=Canopy Growth and Mettrum Announce Respective Shareholder Approvals of the Plan of Arrangement |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=27 January 2017 |website=Mettrum |access-date=15 February 2017}}</ref> In addition to sales in the domestic market, Canopy Growth began selling medical cannabis products in Germany and Brazil in 2016. The company was described as \"one of the world's \u2013 and Canada's first \u2013 premier exporters of marijuana\" by the ''[[Financial Post]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://business.financialpost.com/midas-letter/canopy-takes-over-mettrum-heres-who-might-be-next-in-its-sights|title=Canopy takes over Mettrum, here's who might be next in its sights|last=MidasLetter|date=1 December 2016|newspaper=[[Financial Post]]|access-date=2 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nCanopy Growth's patient base increased by approximately 260 percent and revenue by about 180 percent in the calendar year 2016 vs. 2015. The increase would have been even greater, but the company had difficulty maintaining adequate stock in some high-demand categories such as mid-to-high THC level products and oils. A report by the ''Financial Post'' indicated that inventory shortfalls have been a problem for many of Canada's licensed medical marijuana producers; this could worsen after recreational marijuana is legalized. When the year end report was released, Canopy Growth's share price fell seven percent to $12.09 on the [[Toronto Stock Exchange]] (ticker WEED).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://business.financialpost.com/commodities/agriculture/canopy-growth-corp-almost-triples-revenue-as-number-of-patients-soars|title=Canopy Growth Corp almost triples revenue as number of patients soars|last=Freeman|first=Sunny|date=14 February 2017|newspaper=[[Financial Post]]|access-date=14 February 2017}}</ref> The December 2016 year end report indicated a profit for the first time in the company's history (3 million in net income). Previously, Canopy Growth had been operating at a loss ($3.3 million in 2015, for example), partly because it was using funds to acquire competitors in preparation for significantly increased cannabis demand by the recreational use market expected to commence in early 2018. In early December 2016, [[Reuters]]' survey of four market analysts had indicated a consensus rating of Buy in early December 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/markets/stocks/news/?q=CGC-T|title=Canopy Growth Corp|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|access-date=2 December 2016|quote=Canopy Growth Corporation, formerly Tweed Marijuana Inc., is a diversified cannabis company.}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, [[Constellation Brands]] announced that it would invest an additional US$4 billion in Canopy Growth Corporation in advance of the legalization of recreational marijuana. The investment will increase its share in the company from 9.9% to 38%. Canopy Growth president Bruce Linton said the additional funds would be used for international expansion and that future marketing plans included products such as cannabis-infused beverages and sleep aids.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/08/15/corona-maker-constellation-ups-bet-on-cannabis-with-4-billion-investm.html|title=Corona beer maker Constellation ups bet on cannabis with $4 billion investment in Canopy Growth|last=Sheetz|first=Michael|date=15 August 2017|work=[[CNBC]]|accessdate=10 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://business.financialpost.com/cannabis/constellation-brands-spending-5-billion-to-increase-stake-in-canopy-growth|title='This is rocket fuel': Constellation Brands spending $5 billion to boost stake in Canopy Growth|last=Pfanner|first=Eric|date=15 August 2017|work=[[Financial Post]]|accessdate=10 August 2017|agency=[[Bloomberg News]]|last2=Owram|first2=Kristine|last3=Skerritt|first3=Jen}}</ref> After the Constellation deal was announced, the market value of Canopy Growth rose to nearly US$12 billion,<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news|url=https://business.financialpost.com/cannabis/with-5-billion-constellation-deal-canopy-growth-is-emerging-as-the-google-of-pot|title=With $5-billion Constellation deal, Canopy Growth is emerging as the Google of pot|last=Owram|first=Kristine|date=22 August 2018|work=[[Financial Post]]|accessdate=23 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/investing/stock/cgc|title=Canopy Growth \n|work=Market Watch|accessdate=23 August 2018|quote=Market Cap $11.19B}}</ref> \nroughly $3.7 billion greater than that of the closest competitor [[Aurora Cannabis]].<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nEarlier in 2018, the second largest producer, Aurora Cannabis, bought competitor [[CanniMed]] in advance of the anticipated growth in the market and announced a plan to acquire MedReleaf.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/aurora-medreleaf-pot-deal-1.4661629|title=Aurora buys MedReleaf to cement status as world's biggest cannabis company \u2013 CBC News|last=Evans|first=Pete|date=14 May 2018|work=[[CBC News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://business.financialpost.com/cannabis/our-eyes-are-on-the-global-market-aurora-acquires-medreleaf-in-largest-cannabis-deal-yet|title='Our eyes are on the global market': Aurora acquires MedReleaf in largest cannabis deal yet|last=Rendell|first=Mark|date=5 June 2018|work=[[Financial Post]]}}</ref> It would have distribution agreements in a number of countries, including Germany, Italy, Brazil, and Australia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/edmonton/2018/05/14/edmontons-aurora-cannabis-buys-medreleaf-for-32-billion-becoming-largest-cannabis-producer-in-the-world.html|title=Edmonton's Aurora Cannabis buys MedReleaf for $3.2-billion, becoming 'largest cannabis producer in the world'|last=Maimann|first=Kevin|date=14 May 2018|work=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref>\n\nBy late September, Tilray, Inc. of [[Nanaimo]], a subsidiary of [[Privateer Holdings]] had reached a market capitalization about US$10 billion making it the third largest cannabis company in the world, after Canopy and Aurora.<ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/09/24/tilray-shares-wipe-out-gains-from-last-weeks-wild-ride.html |title=Pot stock Tilray tumbles, completely wiping out gains from last week's wild surge|publisher=CNBC|date=24 September 2018 |accessdate=26 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019 sales volume===\nAn October 2019 report stated that total cannabis sales for the first seven months of the year were only C$524 million when C$4.34 billion (US$3.29 billion) was forecast a year ago.<ref name=\"owram\">{{cite news|author=Kristine Owram|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-10-15/one-year-in-legal-canadian-pot-fails-to-match-the-hype|title=One Year In, Legal Canadian Pot Fails to Match the Hype|date=15 October 2019|work=Bloomberg News|accessdate=15 October 2019}}</ref> Sales were modest because of the limited number of retail operations in Ontario and Quebec where some 23 million people resided; each province had only 25 outlets, as of October 2019.<ref name=owram/> The relatively high cost of the legal product \u2013 almost double that of the [[black market]] \u2013 and the limited types of product (dried flower and oils) also worked against retail sales.<ref name=owram/> In late 2019, more stores were being opened and a wider range of legal cannabis was becoming available, including edibles, topicals, and [[vaping]] products.<ref name=owram/>\n\nProfitability was a problem however, according to a report in early November 2019 which stated, \"pot stocks down nearly 60 per cent since March highs\". This was leading companies to sell off real estate holdings as a method of raising capital to finance expansion. \n<ref>{{cite web |url=https://business.financialpost.com/real-estate/property-post/pot-companies-shed-real-estate-amid-dearth-of-financing-options |title=https://business.financialpost.com/real-estate/property-post/pot-companies-shed-real-estate-amid-dearth-of-financing-options|date=6 November 2019 |work=Financial Post|access-date=8 November 2019 |quote=Sale-leaseback transactions have stepped in to fill the void, becoming a key financial lifeline for an industry that needs capital to fund expansion.}}</ref>\n\n===Competing with the black market===\nA report in October 2019 by [[Bloomberg News]] painted a bleak picture of the legal cannabis industry. Because of the relatively few retail outlets, especially in Ontario, and the high retail prices, the black market remained persistent. An independent cannabis research firm estimated that the black market accounted for 86% of cannabis sales. On average, on a Canada-wide basis, legal cannabis was selling for about $10.23 per gram versus $5.59 found on the black market according to StatsCan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bnnbloomberg.ca/cannabis-gold-rush-falling-short-amid-lure-of-cheaper-black-market-pot-say-analysts-1.1329064|title=Cannabis 'gold rush' falling short amid cheap black market: Analysts - Article|first=David|last=George-Cosh|date=9 October 2019|website=BNN}}</ref>\n\nOntario, at least, planned to take steps in 2020 to increase the number of retail licenses issued per month to increase the availability of legal cannabis, in order to combat the illicit market.<ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/cannibis-store-cap-1.5394662 Ontario removing cap on number of pot shops, opening up market for retailers]</ref>\n\n===Craft cannabis===\nUnder the ''Cannabis Act'' passed in 2018, only producers licensed by the government are allowed to grow the product. As of early October 2018, there were at least 117 such licensed producers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/legal-cannabis-shortage-looms-1.4845816 |title=Don't delete your dealer's number yet \u2013 legal cannabis shortage looms |publisher =CBC News |access-date=27 October 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAlthough consolidation of the cannabis market in Canada is expected to the point where \"a handful of companies will control the majority of the market\",<ref>{{cite news |last=Wood|first=David|date=19 October 2018|title=The cannabis industry can expect more growth \u2013 and consolidation|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/cannabis/article-the-cannabis-industry-can-expect-more-growth-and-consolidation/ |work=Globe and Mail |access-date=21 October 2018 }}</ref> many claim that there is an important need for smaller craft cannabis producers that are \"more able to adapt to consumer demand\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Campbell|first=Lisa|date=1 July 2018|title=New regulations may spark Canada's craft cannabis revolution|url=https://www.straight.com/cannabis/1097161/new-regulations-may-spark-canadas-craft-cannabis-revolution#|work=The Georgia Straight|access-date=21 October 2018 }}</ref> The craft cannabis industry has been compared to the craft beer industry<ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite web |url=https://licensedproducerscanada.ca/faq/what-is-a-health-canada-licensed-producer|title=Will Craft Cannabis Growers in Canada Succeed Like Craft Brewers?|website=Licensed Producers Canada|access-date=21 October 2018}}</ref> \u2013 smaller producers who are able to experiment more and provide a wider variety to the larger companies, which will likely try to please as many consumers as possible. However, the difference is that the relatively new rise of craft brewers in a mature market is different than craft cannabis starting at the same time as larger producers (for recreational cannabis). This will give larger producers the edge in the short term since those companies have more money.<ref>{{cite news |last=Reid|first=Sarah|date=15 November 2017|title=Small pot producers' plans go up in smoke|url=https://tvo.org/article/current-affairs/small-pot-producers-plans-go-up-in-smoke|work=TVO |access-date=21 October 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe expected buy-in for craft cannabis producers is perhaps slightly higher than craft brewers,<ref name=\"auto5\"/> but there are other barriers to launching a craft cannabis company including the ability to market product. Cannabis marketing will be closer to tobacco marketing (which is prohibited in Canada with few limited exceptions<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tobaccocontrollaws.org/legislation/country/canada/summary|title= Legislation by Country: Canada|website=Tobacco Control Laws|access-date=21 October 2018}}</ref>) cannabis will be sold in plain packaging and traditional advertising such as TV commercials will be prohibited.<ref>{{cite news |last=Delacourt|first=Susan|date=23 June 2017|title=Canadian pot ads? Think beer ads. Then think again: Delacourt|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/insight/2017/06/23/canadian-pot-ads-think-beer-ads-then-think-again-delacourt.html|work=Toronto Star|access-date=21 October 2018 }}</ref> They will likely not even be able to mention things that could be important to the consumer such as where it's grown (i.e., \"buy local\") and if it's organic.<ref>{{cite news |date=19 May 2017|title=Craft cannabis growers in B.C. sound alarm over survival of sector|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/cannabis-growers-bc-sound-alarm-over-sector-1.4670742|work=Canadian Press|access-date=21 October 2018 }}</ref>\n\nFurther, simply selling their product may be difficult. The supply chain is still not entirely clear as it is in the beer industry, but there are ways for craft cannabis producers to sell their product through selling to other micro-processors \u2013 and potentially larger producers \u2013 or applying for a micro-processing licence themselves.<ref name=\"auto6\">{{cite news |last=Efron|first=Sarah|date=22 June 2018|title=Craft cannabis growers say better bud will be key to thriving in the legal market|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/business/small-business/growth/article-craft-cannabis-growers-say-better-bud-will-be-key-to-thriving-in-the/|work=Globe and Mail|access-date=21 October 2018 }}</ref> As of the legalization date, consumers cannot sample or purchase product directly from a craft cannabis producer's storefront as you can with craft beer or buy cannabis from a stall on the side of the road as you might from a farmer. However, [[British Columbia]]'s Public Safety Minister Mike Farnsworth said that the province wouldn't rule out farmers selling direct to consumer.<ref>{{cite news |date=19 May 2017|title=Craft cannabis growers in B.C. sound alarm over survival of sector|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/cannabis-growers-bc-sound-alarm-over-sector-1.4670742|work=CBC|access-date=22 October 2018 }}</ref>\n\nStill, most craft cannabis producers are optimistic. One craft cannabis producer told ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' that \"I think there is a real opportunity there for small independents.\"<ref name=\"auto6\"/> Craft cannabis producers are seen by some as the \"artisans of the industry\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Ross|first=Andrea|date=24 June 2018|title=First comes legal cannabis. Then, say industry insiders, will come the artisan stuff|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/alberta-cannabis-industry-craft-growers-1.4758573|work=CBC|access-date=22 October 2018 }}</ref> who will experiment with strains, increase variety, and produce a quality product that it can sell at a premium.<ref name=\"auto5\"/>\n\n===Stock market volatility===\n{{overly detailed|date=November 2019}}\nAt times in 2016, and in 2017, the stock prices of some producers increased significantly as retail investors became more bullish on this segment of the market but then dropped at a later date.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/inside-the-market/over-50-in-3-days-why-investors-have-pushed-aurora-shares-to-new-highs/article36971073/|title=Up 60% in three days: Why investors are euphoric over Aurora Cannabis shares|last=Bouw|first=Brenda|date=14 November 2017|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref> Between September and mid-November 2017, the typical stock cannabis producer's value increased by 54%, according to Vahan Ajamian of Beacon Securities Ltd. The share price of Canopy Growth, for example, more than doubled in price during the fall of the year, but declined in mid-November while others, such as Aurora Cannabis, increased at the same time during another volatile period.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baystreet.ca/etfs/206/Jump-Into-the-Red-Hot-Cannabis-Market-With-This-ETF|title=Jump into the Red Hot Cannabis Market With This ETF|last=O'Callaghan|first=Ambrose|date=8 November 2017|website=Baystreet.ca}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/canopy-growth-reports-third-quarter-loss-revenue-jumps/article36970222/|title=Canopy Growth's second-quarter loss dampens marijuana stock rally|last=Pellegrini|first=Christina|date=14 November 2017|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> At the time, analysts could not predict the long-term outcome for any company.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-11-14/amid-marijuana-boom-cost-data-leave-analysts-dazed-and-confused|title=Amid Marijuana Boom, Costs Leave Analysts Dazed and Confused|last=Skerritt|first=Jen|date=14 November 2017|website=[[Bloomberg News]]}}</ref> A report by [[Investopedia]] in November said that most cannabis stocks \"can be labeled as penny stocks, so any investment may carry a significantly higher risk component.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investopedia.com/investing/10-canadian-marijuana-stocks/|title=10 Canadian Marijuana Stocks for Your Portfolio|last=Krishna|first=Mrinalini|date=3 August 2018|website=[[Investopedia]]}}</ref>\n\nMarket analysts Matt Bottomley and Neil Maruoka of Canaccord Genuity believe that approximately 3.8 million persons will be recreational users (presumably on a frequent basis) by 2021 with a potential for $6 billion in sales.<ref name=\"Skerrit\"/> These analysts predicted that after legalization, there may be a \"shortfall of supply in the near term\", which is likely to increase the product's selling price. Their prediction was based on the government's strict standards, which have resulted in few producers becoming licensed under the current system.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2016/11/30/canada-marijuana-shortage-legalization_n_13336348.html|title=Canada May Face Marijuana Shortage When It's Legalized: Canaccord|last=Tencer|first=Daniel|date=1 December 2016|website=[[Huffington Post]]|access-date=2 December 2016|quote=Canada's system for licensing marijuana producers is so tough that there likely won't be enough producers to meet demand when the federal Liberals legalize the herb}}</ref>\n\nSome industry observers warned that \"speculation and investor frenzy are fuelling many of the gains\". Other observers pointed out that marijuana company values are high but said that \"the players have real products with real sales that are growing, unlike the many dot-com firms that fed that bubble.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Southwick |first=Reid |date=27 January 2017 |title=Investors dive into marijuana stocks, raising concerns about green bubble |url=https://calgaryherald.com/business/local-business/investors-dive-into-marijuana-stocks-raising-concerns-about-green-bubble |newspaper=Herald |location=Calgary |access-date=15 February 2017}}</ref> Some market analysts voiced concern about the long-term retail price of recreational marijuana; they predict that it will decline over time after legalization because of competition and bulk sales to provincial governments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.financialpost.com/commodities/agriculture/amid-marijuana-boom-cost-data-leave-analysts-dazed-and-confused|title='A mad green rush': As marijuana booms, analysts still hazy on impact of Canadian legalization on costs|date=14 November 2017}}</ref> The probability of reducing prices as producers' costs decline due to economies of scale was confirmed by the head of the federal-provincial task force in late 2017. The government also intends to keep the net cost to the consumer adequately low so as to virtually eliminate the need for an illegal market but \"not so low as to create an incentive for increased use\".<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nCertain investment counsellors also warned clients that marijuana stocks are very risky.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bnnbloomberg.ca/video/investing-in-marijuana-stocks-a-tough-gamble-portfolio-manager~1249335|title=Video - BNN - Business News Network|website=BNN}}</ref> According to Barry Schwartz, chief investment officer at Baskin Wealth Management in Toronto, \"It's not the type of investment we'd ever make\" adding that he would advise anyone who asks about investing in this sector, \"don't do it\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Gibillini |first=Nicole |date=1 December 2016 |title='Don't do it': Marijuana stocks 'very risky' for investors, money manager says |url=http://www.bnn.ca/don-t-do-it-marijuana-stocks-very-risky-for-investors-money-manager-warns-1.621309 |publisher=BNN/Bell Media |location=Toronto |access-date=2 December 2016}}</ref> In spite of the significant increases in the stock prices of several cannabis producers in early November 2017, few institutional investors were buying such shares because of the uncertainty as to which would succeed and which would fail.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bnnbloomberg.ca/commodities/video/cannabis-not-a-market-most-institutional-investors-want-to-get-into-says-portfolio-s-levine~1257277|title=Video|website=BNN}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, business columnist David Olive of the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' strongly recommended against investing in this industry. His rationale includes these aspects: there are too many producers for the small Canadian market (\"close to 100 players\"), retail prices will drop significantly, reducing margins, and the expense ratio is excessively high, so most companies will not be profitable. \"Only the most risk-tolerant and speculative-minded investors should go anywhere near it,\" he warned.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2017/11/17/6-reasons-an-investment-in-the-pot-industry-will-likely-go-up-in-smoke-olive.html|title=6 reasons an investment in the pot industry will likely go up in smoke: Olive|first=David|last=Olive|date=17 November 2017|work=Toronto Star}}</ref>\n\nThe promise of legalization boosted the share price of marijuana growers on the Toronto Stock Exchange in November and December 2017.<ref>[http://mjinews.com/marijuana-index-gains-continue-pot-stock/ \"Marijuana Index Gains Continue As Pot Stocks Anticipate Prohibition Repeal\"], ''MJI News''.</ref> A market analyst explained that the confidence was based on the fact that legal marijuana will not be more expensive, with tax included, than the black market product; this should ensure a sizeable market for producers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bnn.ca/marijuana-stocks-rally-following-ottawa-s-proposed-dollar-a-gram-tax-1.912096|title=Marijuana stocks rally following Ottawa's proposed dollar-a-gram tax|date=10 November 2017|publisher=BNN}}</ref> Advertising will probably be used to boost sales. The federal task force had recommended that restrictions on ad content should be similar to those for tobacco ads, extremely stringent. The cannabis producers' lobby group, however, was proposing the gentler restrictions that apply to alcohol producers: not to appeal to youth and to promote only the brand, not the recreational use of the product.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/business/marijuana-producers-want-advertising-rules-akin-to-alcohol-not-cigarettes-1.3674405|title=Marijuana producers want advertising rules akin to alcohol, not cigarettes|date=12 November 2017|publisher=CTV News}}</ref>\n\nAs the stock markets approached the year-end closing in 2017, the price of major cannabis stocks surged but [[Bloomberg News]] reported that \"some analysts are skeptical about demand projections, and betting against the stocks is difficult to do\" because there was \"almost no stock left to short, and some investors who have taken short positions in the market have lost money\", quoting Ihor Dusaniwsky of S3 Partners (investment analysts) in New York.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> The BCMI Cannabis Report<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bnn.ca/video/marijuana-stocks-pull-back-from-peak-is-this-a-concern-for-investors~1029855|title=Video \u2013 BNN \u2013 Business News Network|website=BNN}}</ref> warned that the boom could \"end badly\", with the bubble bursting as other industries' \"manias\" had burst in the past.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-12-14/why-it-s-so-difficult-to-bet-against-canada-s-marijuana-boom|title=Why It's So Hard to Bet Against Canada's Marijuana Boom|date=14 December 2017|via=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref>\n\n====Developments in 2018 and 2019====\nOn 4 January 2018, a plunge in prices was being reported by Bloomberg.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.financialpost.com/investing/pot-stocks-plunge-on-report-that-u-s-is-axing-policy-that-lets-legal-marijuana-flourish|title=Pot stocks plunge as Trump administration moves to weaken marijuana legalization movement|date=4 January 2018}}</ref> An update by [[Forbes]] in mid-July 2018 indicated that year to date, the Canadian Marijuana (stock) Index had declined by 19.1%, but had gained 132% over the previous year.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alanjbrochstein/2018/07/14/canadian-cannabis-stocks-weighed-down-by-capital-raises-and-new-issues/#5f9b42fd4a4a|title=Canadian Cannabis Stocks Weighed Down By Capital Raises And New Issues|date=14 July 2018|magazine=Forbes}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, [[Constellation Brands]] (a beer, wine and spirits producer) announced that it would invest an additional C$5 billion (US$3.8 billion) in Canopy Growth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/cannabis/2018/08/15/constellation-brands-invests-5b-to-boost-stake-in-pot-producer-canopy-growth.html|title=Constellation Brands invests $5B to boost stake in pot producer Canopy Growth|date=15 August 2018|website=thestar.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://business.financialpost.com/cannabis/constellation-brands-spending-5-billion-to-increase-stake-in-canopy-growth|title='This is rocket fuel': Constellation Brands spending $5 billion to boost stake in Canopy Growth|date=15 August 2018}}</ref> After the Constellation deal, the market value of Canopy Growth rose to US$11 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://business.financialpost.com/cannabis/with-5-billion-constellation-deal-canopy-growth-is-emerging-as-the-google-of-pot|title=With $5-billion Constellation deal, Canopy Growth is emerging as the Google of pot|website=Financial Post|accessdate=23 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 September 2018, Tilray Inc. (TLRY:US on NASDAQ) of [[Nanaimo]], a subsidiary or [[Privateer Holdings]], became the world's largest cannabis company in terms of market capitalisation, after a 77% increase in its stock price.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4469273/b-c-based-tilray-becomes-most-valuable-cannabis-company-after-stock-spikes-as-high-as-1600-per-cent/ |title=B.C.-based Tilray becomes most valuable cannabis company after stock spikes as high as 1,600 per cent|publisher=Bloomberg |date=20 September 2018 |accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"auto7\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-09-19/thiel-backed-fund-hits-jackpot-with-12-billion-tilray-stake |title=Peter Thiel-Backed Fund Hits the Jackpot With $12 Billion Tilray Stake|publisher=Bloomberg |date=19 September 2018 |accessdate=20 September 2018}}</ref> However, the share price dropped significantly over the next few days, reducing Tilray's market capitalisation to about US$10 billion compared to the earlier $19+ billion value.<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\nExperts interviewed by [[Global News]] in mid-September continued to warn about market volatility.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4460887/canada-weed-stocks-skyrocketing-investing/ |title=Canadian weed stocks are skyrocketing as legalization looms: But should you invest? |publisher=Global News |date=18 September 2018 |accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nAn October 2019 report stated that cannabis stocks had \"crumbled to their lowest level since 2017\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://business.financialpost.com/cannabis/cannabis-business/cannabis-investing/cannabis-stocks-crumble-to-2017-lows-after-hexo-latest-to-lower-earnings-expectations |title=Cannabis stocks crumble to 2017 lows after Hexo becomes latest to lower earnings expectations |date=10 October 2019 |work=Financial Post|access-date=16 November 2019 |quote=Tilray fell as much 12 per cent, heading for a record low. Canopy slid 9.7 per cent, Aurora lost 5.9 per cent and Cronos Group Inc. fell 6.7 per cent.}}</ref> A report on the market by [[Forbes]] provided this assessment of the situation:<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alanjbrochstein/2019/10/27/cannabis-stocks-now-appeal-to-value-investors/#3878be9d5e8d |title=Cannabis Stocks Now Appeal To Value Investors |date=27 October 2019 |magazine=Forbes |access-date=16 November 2019 |quote=While the capital markets aren\u2019t entirely closed to cannabis companies, the ability to raise equity at reasonable prices has greatly diminished. Investors have responded by sending prices to multi-year lows. The broad sell-off has hit all stocks, but some companies have better balance sheets and operating models than others.}}</ref> <blockquote>2019 has been an extremely disappointing year for investors in cannabis stocks, with the overall market, as measured by the New Cannabis Ventures Global Cannabis Stock Index down 20% after a 55% decline in 2018. The market, which has declined over 71% since early 2018, has moved to three-year lows. The current environment is challenging, as funding has dried up ... Many companies won\u2019t make it or will have to raise capital on extremely unfavorable terms...\"</blockquote>\n\n====Excise tax and sales tax====\n{{Update section|date=September 2018}}\nFrom the early planning stages, the government indicated that the substance would be taxed. An estimate in late 2016 suggested revenues of $618 million per year from a federal tax initially, and eventually, billions, according to a report by Canada's [[Parliamentary Budget Officer]] (PBO).<ref name=\"Cullen\"/> (A recent government estimate indicates that the illegal marijuana industry is worth $7 billion per year.<ref>{{cite news |last=Cryderman |first=Kelley |date=27 November 2016 |title=Report on Canada's marijuana legalization due this week |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/report-on-marijuana-legalization-in-canada-due-this-week/article33065608/ |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |location=Toronto |access-date=2 December 2016}}</ref>) The Task Force report recommended that high-potency cannabis (with a high THC content) be taxed at a higher level than the conventional product to make it less attractive to consumers.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web |url=https://ipolitics.ca/2016/12/13/set-minimum-legal-age-for-marijuana-at-18-says-task-force/ |title=Set minimum legal age for marijuana at 18, says task force |last=Duggan |first=Kyle |date=13 December 2016 |website=iPolitics |publisher=iPolitics |access-date=15 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/federal-task-force-advises-wide-ranging-legalization-of-recreational-marijuana/article33307322/ |title=Federal task force advises wide-ranging legalization of recreational marijuana |last=LeBlanc |first=Daniel |date=13 December 2017 |website=The Globe and Mail |access-date=13 December 2016 |quote=The group of experts, chaired by former Liberal minister Anne McLellan, is also recommending that high-potency products be more heavily taxed, to \"discourage\" their use in the general public.}}</ref>\n\nThe federal government had announced in October 2017 that its budget would include $546 million over five years to prepare the \"legal framework to strictly regulate and restrict access to cannabis\" and another $150 million over six years to enforce the restrictions on drug-impaired driving.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/news/politics/canadas-new-budget-numbers-show-booming-economic-growth-and-booming-spending|title=Canada's new budget numbers show booming economic growth \u2013 and booming spending|date=25 October 2017}}</ref> Health Canada and the Royal Canadian Mounted Police will receive a share of the funds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-26/rolling-out-legal-weed-comes-with-a-high-price-tag-for-canada|title=Rolling Out Legal Weed Comes With a High Price Tag for Canada|date=26 October 2017|via=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref> Of this amount, municipal and indigenous police services should receive $81 million to offset the increased cost of training and resources.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.financialpost.com/commodities/agriculture/ottawa-proposing-legal-weed-tax-of-at-least-1-per-gram-plus-gst|title=Marijuana stocks rally as Ottawa proposes legal weed tax of at least $1 per gram, plus GST|date=10 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 November 2017, the government announced that the federal excise tax, to be shared 50/50 with the provinces and territories, should not exceed $1 a gram or 10 per cent of the producer's price, whichever is higher. The government's press released did not specify higher tax on high-potency products.<ref name=Globe>Mike Hager and Carrie Tait, [https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/british-columbia/provinces-keep-lucrative-online-market-for-legal-marijuana-tothemselves/article37019186/ \"Provinces to keep control of online cannabis sales\"], 18 November 2017.</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> In December 2017, after demands from provinces for a higher percentage, a two-year agreement was signed to provide a full 75% of the tax; as well, the maximum to be taken by the federal government would be $100 million per annum, with any excess paid to the provinces and territories. The final retail price of the product will include provincial sales tax,<ref name=\":0\" /> ranging from 5% to 15% depending on the province.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> This arrangement will be discussed again in December 2018 to determine whether the five months of experience indicated that the 75/25 tax splitting scheme had proved to be appropriate.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Caroline Cahill |title=Finance Ministers Revise Canadian Cannabis Tax Plan |url=http://mjinews.com/finance-ministers-canadian-cannabis-tax-plan/ |website=mjinews.com}}</ref>\n\n== Regulation by province ==\n{{see|Cannabis laws of Canada by province or territory}}\n[[File:2018 British Columbia advertisement of cannabis use.jpg|thumb|Government public service advertisement about the effects of cannabis use in [[Vancouver]].]]\nIn Canada, regulation varies province to province, though there are some general rules regarding promotion, packaging, and advertising. Adult-use cannabis can only be sold in packages of a single colour without graphics other than the logo and a health warning.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2018/06/08/marijuana-industry-seeks-creative-ways-to-brand-product.html|title=Marijuana industry seeks 'creative ways' to brand product|last=Bissett|first=Kevin|date=8 June 2018|work=[[Toronto Star]]|access-date=22 July 2018|agency=[[The Canadian Press]]}}</ref> Cannabis companies in Canada will not be allowed to promote themselves through TV commercials, billboards, or glossy magazine ads, sponsor people or events, or put their names on sports and cultural facilities. To address these advertising challenges, some brands are connecting with popular media influencers like [[Gene Simmons]] and the [[Trailer Park Boys]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/pot-packages|title=Rock stars, actors getting in on Canada's race to legal weed|last=Miller|first=Jacquie|date=3 April 2018|work=[[Ottawa Citizen]]|access-date=22 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Cannabis Act'' (2018) gave provinces the power to determine the method of distribution and sale and whether cannabis use will be legal inside private residence or homes if children are present in the home 12 or more hours in a day,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/provincial-marijuana-sales-retail-1.4167735|title=As provinces seek the 'right' price for pot, how it's sold could matter|last=Israel|first=Solomon|date=20 June 2017|work=[[CBC News]]}}</ref> and each will also establish the legal age for cannabis use.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/liberal-legal-marijuana-pot-1.4041902|title=Liberals to announce marijuana will be legal by July 1, 2018|last=Cochrane|first=David|date=26 March 2017|work=[[CBC News]]|access-date=28 March 2017}}</ref> An [[Excise Tax|excise tax]] will be levied, to be shared with the provinces and territories.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/pot-joe-ceci-cannabis-finance-ministers-excise-taxes-1.4443836|title=New cannabis deal an improvement but legal pot won't be a revenue generator, Alberta finance minister predicts|last=Bellefontaine|first=Michelle|date=11 December 2017|work=[[CBC News]]|access-date=}}</ref> According to the federal government, estimated annual sales will be $4 billion (US$3.2b).<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-01-02/taxes-could-help-canada-keep-its-legal-marijuana-prices-in-check|title=Taxes Could Help Canada Keep Its Legal Marijuana Prices in Check|last=Wingrove|first=Josh|date=2 January 2018|work=[[Bloomberg News]]}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Cannabis Act'' (2018) also allows householders to grow up to four cannabis plants, but [[Quebec]] and [[Manitoba]] announced that they would not permit this option.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/3867467/marijuana-legalization-canada-progress/|title=Just months away, here's how pot legalization is shaping up in Canada|last=Paperny|first=Anna Mehler|date=17 November 2017|work=[[Global News]]|access-date=|agency=[[Reuters]]|last2=Saminather|first2=Nichola}}</ref> [[New Brunswick]] is specifying indoor growing only in a separate locked space, but will also allow outdoor growing for plants that are up to 1.52m (5 feet) high.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4238754/quebec-ban-marijuana-home-grows/|title=Why marijuana legalization will likely include bans on home grows|last=Cain|first=Patrick|date=29 May 2018|work=[[Global News]]|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://thehighinvestor.ca/2018/10/02/new-cannabis-regulations-explained-by-province/|title=New Cannabis Regulations Explained \u2013 By Province|date=2 October 2018|work=The High Investor|access-date=7 October 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nMost provinces have set the minimum age to purchase and consume cannabis to 19 years old, although Alberta and Quebec have set it to 18 years old in line with their alcohol and tobacco laws.<ref name=\":3\" /> Manitoba is currently the only province or territory where the legal cannabis age is not identical to the alcohol and tobacco purchase age (19 for cannabis vs. 18 for alcohol/tobacco).<ref>https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/legal-pot-age-19-wrong-message-manitoba-1.4435236</ref>\n\nUnder the newly elected [[Coalition Avenir Qu\u00e9bec]] government, the Deputy Minister for Health in October 2018, [[Lionel Carmant]] announced that the Government will tighten the rules on cannabis consumption, including increasing the legal age to consume to 21 from 18.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/quebec/caq-wants-to-hike-legal-age-for-cannabis-to-21-by-march-minister-says|title=CAQ wants to hike legal age for cannabis to 21 by March, minister says|date=25 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://montreal.ctvnews.ca/cannabis-at-21-quebec-confirms-it-will-raise-age-asap-1.4148095|title=Cannabis at 21: Quebec confirms it will raise age ASAP|date=24 October 2018}}</ref> In 2019, CAQ announced Quebec will also ban the sale of cannabis candies and desserts, including chocolate. because federal cannabis regulations don't go far enough in protecting children from accidentally consuming the drug.<ref>https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/cannabis-regulations-quebec-legal-1.5223723</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/5679335/quebec-to-ban-sale-of-cannabis-candies-in-effort-to-protect-kids/|title=Quebec to ban sale of cannabis candies in effort to protect kids|website=Global News}}</ref>\n\n==Military==\n{{main|Cannabis and the Canadian military}}\nIn early September 2018, the Canadian government released a directive stating that service members will be allowed to use cannabis following legalization in October, but with restrictions on use depending on the individual's duties.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/janetwburns/2018/09/11/canadas-military-green-lights-adult-cannabis-use-for-most-personnel/#2dd92e2875a3|title=Canadian Military Green-Lights Cannabis Use For Most Personnel|first=Janet|last=Burns}}</ref> Per the new regulations, service members may use legal cannabis, but must cease usage:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-canada-cannabis-military/canadas-military-unveils-rules-governing-troop-cannabis-use-idUSKCN1LN29V|title=Canada's military unveils rules governing troop cannabis use|first=Anna Mehler|last=Paperny}}</ref>\n\n* 8 hours prior to duty: all personnel\n* 24 hours prior to duty: anyone operating a weapon or vehicle\n* 28 days before duty: members involved in high-risk activities such as [[high altitude]] parachuting, operating in a [[hyperbaric]] environment, and serving on military aircraft\n*on international operations\n\n==See also==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n* [[Cannabis in Alberta]]\n* [[Cannabis in British Columbia]]\n* [[Cannabis in Manitoba]]\n* [[Cannabis in New Brunswick]]\n* [[Cannabis in Newfoundland and Labrador]]\n* [[Cannabis in the Northwest Territories]]\n* [[Cannabis in Nova Scotia]]\n{{col-break}}\n{{Col-2}}\n{{portal|Canada|Cannabis}}\n* [[Cannabis in Nunavut]]\n* [[Cannabis in Ontario]]\n* [[Cannabis in Prince Edward Island]]\n* [[Cannabis in Quebec]]\n* [[Cannabis in Saskatchewan]]\n* [[Cannabis in Yukon]]\n* [[Cannabis on Canadian Indian reserves]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last1 = Nolin |first1 = Pierre Claude|last2= Kenny|first2=Colin |year =2003 |title =Cannabis: Report of the Senate Special Committee on Illegal Drugs\n |url =https://books.google.com/books?id=L_5gu-eUfE8C&pg=PP1#v=twopage&q&f=true |publisher= University of Toronto Press |isbn=0-8020-8946-1}}\n* {{cite book|author=Kyle Grayson|title=Chasing Dragons: Security, Identity, and Illicit Drugs in Canada|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KUQHs7XNZ2AC&pg=PP1#v=twopage&q&f=true |date=12 April 2008|publisher=University of Toronto Press|isbn=978-0-8020-9479-7}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.ccsa.ca/Resource%20Library/CCSA-Canadian-Drug-Summary-Cannabis-2018-en.pdf|publisher=Canadian Centre on Substance Use and Addiction |title=Cannabis (Canadian Drug Summary) |date=June 2018}}\n*Ryan Macdonald; Michelle Rotermann, ( 2017) {{cite book|url=https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/n1/pub/11-626-x/11-626-x2017077-eng.htm|title=Experimental Estimates of Cannabis Consumption in Canada, 1960 to 2015 |publisher=Statistics Canada \u2013 Economic Analysis Division and Health Analysis Division}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Cannabis in Canada}}\n* [http://www.parl.gc.ca/common/Committee_SenHome.asp?Language=E&Parl=37&Ses=1&comm_id=85 2002 Canadian Senate Special Committee on Illicit Drugs]\n* [http://www2.parl.gc.ca/HousePublications/Publication.aspx?pub=bill&doc=C-38&parl=37&ses=2&language=E Failed decriminalization bill]\n* [http://www.druglibrary.org/schaffer/Library/studies/ledain/ldctoc.html The Report of the Canadian Government Commission of Inquiry into the Non-Medical Use of Drugs \u2013 1972] \u2013 LeDain Commission Report\n* [http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/dhp-mps/marihuana/info/list-eng.php Authorized Licensed Producers under the Marihuana for Medical Purposes Regulations]\n* [http://www.statcan.gc.ca/pub/13-610-x/13-610-x2018001-eng.htm Cannabis Statistics Hub]\n\n{{Cannabis in Canada}}\n{{Navboxes \n|list=\n{{Marijuana Party of Canada}}\n{{Americas topic|Cannabis in}}\n{{Cannabis by country}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cannabis in Canada}}\n[[Category:Cannabis by country|Canada]]\n[[Category:Cannabis in Canada| ]]\n[[Category:Legal history of Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Canadian English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Cannabis in Canada sidebar}}\n'''Cannabis in Canada''' is legal for both [[cannabis (drug)|recreational]] and [[Medical cannabis|medicinal]] purposes. Medicinal use of [[cannabis]] was legalized nationwide on 30 July 2001 under conditions outlined in the [[Marihuana for Medical Purposes Regulations]], later superseded by the Access to Cannabis for Medical Purposes Regulations,<ref name=\"Access to Cannabis for Medical Purposes Regulations (SOR/2016-230)\">{{cite web|url=http://laws.justice.gc.ca/eng/regulations/SOR-2016-230/ |title=Access to Cannabis for Medical Purposes Regulations |publisher=laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/ |accessdate=20 March 2017}}</ref> issued by [[Health Canada]] and seed, grain, and fibre production was permitted under licence by Health Canada.<ref name=\"Hemp Laws\">{{cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/health-canada/services/health-concerns/controlled-substances-precursor-chemicals/industrial-hemp/about-hemp-canada-hemp-industry/frequently-asked-questions.html|title=Industrial Hemp Regulation Program FAQ|date=November 2012|publisher=Health Canada|accessdate=30 October 2013}}</ref> The federal ''[[Cannabis Act]]'' came into effect on 17 October 2018 and made Canada the second country in the world, after [[Uruguay]], to formally legalize the cultivation, possession, acquisition and consumption of cannabis and its [[Cannabis (drug)#Preparations|by-products]].<!--Whereas decriminalization would simply remove laws restricting the use of cannabis products, as has been implemented in many countries, legalization allows for the taxation of legally produced cannabis--><ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/06/20/health/canada-legalizes-marijuana/index.html|title=Canada becomes second nation in the world to legalize marijuana|last=Sapra|first=Bani|date=20 June 2018|work=[[CNN]]|access-date=}}</ref> Canada is the first [[G7]] and [[G20]] nation to do so.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jun/06/all-eyes-on-canada-as-first-g7-nation-prepares-to-make-marijuana-legal|title=All eyes on Canada as first G7 nation prepares to make marijuana legal|last=Ross|first=Selena|date=6 June 2018|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nCannabis was banned in Canada from 1923 until regulated medical cannabis became legal on 30 July 2001. In response to popular opinion,<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/2995390/canada-will-see-900000-new-pot-smokers-under-legalization-poll-implies/|title=Canada will see 900,000 new pot smokers under legalization, poll implies|last=Cain|first=Patrick|date=12 October 2016|work=[[Global News]]|access-date=4 February 2017}}</ref> the legislation to legalize cannabis for recreational use (''[[Cannabis Act]]'', Bill C-45) was passed by the [[House of Commons of Canada]] on 27 November 2017; it passed second reading in the [[Senate of Canada]] on 22 March 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nationalpost.com/cannabis/cp-newsalert-senate-backs-bill-to-legalize-recreational-marijuana|title=Bill to legalize marijuana passes second reading in Senate as Conservatives drop threat to block it|last=Vaughan|first=Andrew|date=23 March 2018|work=[[National Post]]|accessdate=23 June 2018|agency=[[The Canadian Press]]}}</ref> On 18 June 2018, the House passed the bill with most, but not all, of the Senate's amendments.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/policy/international/392846-canadas-house-of-commons-votes-to-legalize-marijuana|title=Canada's House of Commons votes to legalize marijuana|last=Anapol|first=Avery|date=18 June 2018|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|access-date=19 June 2018}}</ref> The Senate accepted this version of the Act the following day.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4282677/pot-bill-senate-passes/|title=Marijuana legalization Bill C-45 officially passes Senate vote, heading for royal assent|last=Scotti|first=Monique|date=19 June 2018|work=[[Global News]]}}</ref>\n\nThe federal government announced that recreational use of cannabis would no longer violate criminal law as of 17 October 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/cannabis-pot-legalization-bill-1.4713839|title=Trudeau says pot will be legal as of Oct. 17, 2018|last=Tasker|first=John Paul|date=20 June 2018|work=[[CBC News]]|access-date=}}</ref> This legalization comes with regulation similar to that of [[Alcoholic drinks in Canada|alcohol in Canada]], limiting home production, distribution, consumption areas and sale times.<ref name=\"Justice\">{{cite web |title=Cannabis Act (S.C. 2018, c. 16) |url=https://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/C-24.5/index.html |website=Justice Canada |publisher=Government of Canada |accessdate=24 November 2018}}</ref> The process removed cannabis possession for personal consumption from the [[Controlled Drugs and Substances Act]]; while implementing taxation and strengthen punishment of those convicted of either supplying cannabis to minors, or of impairment while driving a motor vehicle.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/tax-on-legalized-pot-won-t-be-a-cash-cow-pm-1.2704748|title=Tax on legalized pot won't be a cash cow: PM|last=Bronskill|first=Jim|date=17 December 2015|work=[[CTV News]]|access-date=23 December 2015|agency=[[The Canadian Press]]}}</ref>\n\nAs of January 2019, on-line sales of cannabis for recreational use were well underway across Canada, via the provincial or territorial governments. Most provinces also had storefront operations selling cannabis, either operated by the government or private enterprise. The number of retailers is likely to remain limited, largely due to insufficient supply of legal cannabis from licensed producers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/cannabis/2019/01/10/ontario-is-holding-a-lottery-for-cannabis-stores-on-friday-heres-what-the-rest-of-the-country-tried-and-how-it-turned-out.html|title=Ontario is holding a lottery for cannabis stores on Friday. Here's what the rest of the country tried and how it turned out|date=10 January 2019 |work=Toronto Star|accessdate=11 January 2019\n}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{main|Legal history of cannabis in Canada}}\n[[File:BlackCandle.jpg|thumb|200px|The cover of Murphy's 1922 book ''The Black Candle'', that claimed \"marijuana turned its users into homicidal maniacs.\"<ref name=\"BrunoCsiernik2018\">{{cite book|author1=Tara L. Bruno|author2=Rick Csiernik|title=The Drug Paradox: An Introduction to the Sociology of Psychoactive Substances in Canada|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hbpaDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA21|year=2018|publisher=Canadian Scholars|isbn=978-1-77338-052-0|page=21}}</ref>]]\nDrug prohibition in Canada began with the Opium Act of 1908.<ref name=\"McCormickMcCormick2005\">{{cite book|author1=Christopher Ray McCormick|author2=Chris McCormick|author3=Len Green|title=Crime and Deviance in Canada: Historical Perspectives|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NcVZPgwoNvoC&pg=PA355|year=2005|publisher=Canadian Scholars' Press|isbn=978-1-55130-274-4|page=355}}</ref> Historians often point to the 1922 publication of [[Emily Murphy]]'s ''The Black Candle''  as the catalyst for the addition of the three extra drugs to a list of prohibited substances.<ref name=\"Lee2012\">{{cite book|author=Martin A. Lee|title=Smoke Signals: A Social History of Marijuana \u2013 Medical, Recreational and Scientific|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n-SG3oWUjhMC&pg=PA325|date=14 August 2012|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4391-0260-2|pages=325}}</ref> Murphy's anti-drug screeds were widely read and helped spread the drug panic across the country, historian Catharine Carstairs disputes that the seven-page chapter, \"Marahuana -- a new menace\" inspired the inclusion of cannabis as a restricted substance.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/obj/s4/f2/dsk4/etd/MQ81078.pdf |title=The Grandmother of Marijuana Prohibition |last=House |first=Yolande |date=May 2003 |website=Collections Canada |publisher=Government of Canada |access-date=18 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/health/marijuana-was-criminalized-in-1923-but-why-1.2630436|title=A Canadian mystery: Why was pot criminalized in 1923? |publisher=- CBC News}}</ref>\n\nCannabis was made illegal when it was added to the country's Confidential Restricted List in 1923 under the ''Narcotics Drug Act Amendment Bill'' after a vague reference to a \"new drug\" during a late night session of the House of Commons on 23 April 1923.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/health/marijuana-was-criminalized-in-1923-but-why-1.2630436|title=Marijuana was criminalized in 1923, but why?|last=Daniel|first=Schartz|date=3 May 2014|work=[[CBC News]]|accessdate=29 July 2014|quote=The only mention of the proposed changes to the schedule recorded in Hansard was on 23 April, when Beland told the House of Commons, \"There is a new drug in the schedule.\"}}</ref> According to one government official, cannabis was outlawed after the Director of the Federal Division of Narcotic Control returned from [[League of Nations]] meetings where the international control of cannabis was broached.<ref name=\"Carstairs\">{{cite journal|last=Carstairs|first=Catherine|year=2000|title='Hop Heads' and 'Hypes': Drug Use, Regulation and Resistance in Canada, 1920\u20131961|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/obj/s4/f2/dsk2/ftp03/NQ53757.pdf|version=PhD dissertation|publisher=University of Toronto|accessdate=2 January 2008}}</ref>{{rp|49}} Cannabis did not begin to attract official attention in Canada until the later 1930s, and even then it was minimal.<ref name=\"Carstairs\" />{{rp|51}} The first seizure of cannabis by Canadian police was not made until 1937.<ref name=\"Carstairs\" />{{rp|48}} Commercial cultivation of [[industrial hemp]] was forbidden in 1938.<ref>{{cite book|title=Textile Horizons|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8uPxAAAAMAAJ|year=2005|publisher=ITBD|page=119}}</ref> Between 1946 and 1961, cannabis accounted for only 2% of all drug arrests in Canada.<ref name=\"Carstairs\" />{{rp|112}}\n\nIn the 1960s, cannabis arrests began to increase rapidly in Canada. For the entire period of 1930\u20131946, the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police|RCMP]] recorded only 25 cannabis arrests, but this rose to 2,300 cases in 1968, and to 12,000 cases in 1972.<ref name=\"DrugsKenny2003\">{{cite book|author1=Canada. Parliament. Senate. Special Committee on Illegal Drugs|author2=Colin Kenny|author3=Pierre Claude Nolin|title=Cannabis: Report of the Senate Special Committee on Illegal Drugs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L_5gu-eUfE8C&pg=PA59|year=2003|publisher=University of Toronto Press|isbn=978-0-8020-8630-3|pages=59}}</ref> In response to the increased popularization of marijuana and the increase in criminal charges against middle class citizens, the government formed the Royal Commission of Inquiry into the Non-Medical Use of Drugs, usually referred to as the [[Le Dain Commission]], in 1969 to investigate non-medical cannabis use in Canada.<ref name=\"RutherdaleFahrni2008\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8uKz-8jB4WsC&pg=PA318|title=Creating Postwar Canada: Community, Diversity, and Dissent, 1945\u201375|date=1 July 2008|publisher=[[UBC Press]]|isbn=978-0-7748-5815-1|editor-last=Rutherdale|editor-first=Robert|pages=318\u2013|editor-last2=Fahrni|editor-first2=Magda}}</ref> The commission's 1972 report recommended removing criminal penalties for cannabis possession, though not legalization, per se. While the subsequent two federal governments discussed the recommendation, no steps were actually taken to change legislation.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hathaway|first=Andrew D.|date=2009|title=The Legal History and Cultural Experience of Cannabis|url=http://www.heretohelp.bc.ca/sites/default/files/visions_cannabis.pdf|journal=Visions|volume=5|issue=4|pages=12\u201313|access-date=16 December 2016|quote=In Canada, the government rejected the Le Dain proposal to remove criminal penalties for cannabis possession.}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, the country started a medical marijuana program, managed by [[Health Canada]]. The program originally offered people access to home grown cannabis or sales directly from Health Canada. This was replaced with new regulations that set up a more traditional commercial sector for cannabis cultivation and distribution in 2013.<ref>{{cite news |title=A timeline of some significant events in the history of medical marijuana in Canada |url=https://london.ctvnews.ca/medicalmarijuana/a-timeline-of-some-significant-events-in-the-history-of-medical-marijuana-in-canada-1.3858860 |accessdate=13 November 2018 |work=The Canadian Press, CTV News-London |date=2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.leafly.com/news/canada/guide-to-canada-medical-marijuana-program|title=A Guide to Canada's Medical Marijuana Program {{!}} Leafly|date=28 June 2017|work=Leafly|access-date=12 November 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Steps to legalization ==\n{{See|Cannabis Act}}\nAfter he was elected Prime Minister in 2015, the first significant step that [[Justin Trudeau]] took was the creation of a federal-provincial-territorial task force to discuss a jointly suitable process for the legalization of cannabis possession for casual use. This Task Force on Marijuana Legalization and Regulation released a 106-page report to the public on 13 December 2016, with various recommendations. Those were provided for consideration by the federal and provincial governments, but they were not binding.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bnnbloomberg.ca/ottawa-to-release-task-force-report-on-marijuana-legalization-1.630354|title=Task force recommends setting 18 as minimum age for pot purchases|author=The Canadian Press<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=13 December 2016|website=BNN|publisher=Bell Media|access-date=13 December 2016|quote=recreational marijuana should not be sold in the same location as alcohol or tobacco}}</ref> Sales for recreational use were not to commence until 1 July 2018, at the earliest, based on legislation (Bill C-45, the ''Cannabis Act'') passed by the federal government in June 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ipolitics.ca/2017/11/27/house-passes-pot-legalization-bill-senate-wild-card/|title=House passes pot legalization bill \u2013 but Senate could be a 'wild card'|last=Duggan|first=Kyle|date=27 November 2017|website=iPolitics}}</ref>\n\nThe substance remains controlled: sold only at government licensed retailers, and grown only by licensed producers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2016/11/14/shoppers-drug-mart-right-spot-to-sell-medicinal-pot-poll.html|title=Shoppers Drug Mart right spot to sell medicinal pot: poll|last=Wright|first=Lisa|date=14 November 2016|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|access-date=4 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/2987372/how-will-legal-pot-be-sold-liquor-stores-are-most-likely-option/|title=How will legal pot be sold? Three things that might happen, and one that won't|last=Cain|first=Patrick|date=9 October 2016|work=[[Global News]]|access-date=1 December 2016}}</ref> During the federal election campaign, the Liberals had promised \"new, stronger laws\" against sales to minors, driving while impaired, and sales through channels not specifically authorized to do so.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/marijuana-advisory-panel-report-questions-1.3872633|title=8 burning questions about the coming federal pot report|last=Cullen|first=Catherine|date=30 November 2016|work=[[CBC News]]|access-date=30 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nUntil 17 October 2018, cannabis remained illegal (except with a physician's prescription, for medical purposes), as Trudeau reminded police forces across the country in late 2016. He insisted that they \"enforce the law\": criminally charge illegal storefront dispensaries. Trudeau also explained that the intent of the legislation is not to encourage recreational use of cannabis. The intent is \"to better protect our kids from the easy access they have right now to marijuana [and] to remove the criminal elements that were profiting from marijuana\", he told the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' on 2 December 2016.<ref name=\"Benzie\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/queenspark/2016/12/03/trudeau-urges-police-to-enforce-the-law-on-marijuana.html|title=Trudeau urges police to 'enforce the law' on marijuana|last=Benzie|first=Robert|date=3 December 2016|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|access-date=4 December 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Marc Emery and Jodie Emery.JPG|thumb|[[Marc Emery|Marc]] and [[Jodie Emery]], Canadian [[cannabis rights]] activists.]]\nPolice forces took the Prime Minister seriously, and in March 2017, raided five locations of the Cannabis Culture retailer in [[Toronto]], one in [[Vancouver]], and another in [[Hamilton, Ontario]]. They also searched homes in Toronto, [[Stoney Creek, Ontario|Stoney Creek]], and Vancouver. Multiple charges were laid against [[Marc Emery]] and [[Jodie Emery]], owners of [[Cannabis Culture (magazine)|Cannabis Culture]], a company that franchised pot dispensary shops. The couple was convicted in December 2017 of drug-related charges, including possession of marijuana for the purpose of trafficking; fined; and placed on two years of probation.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news|url=https://nationalpost.com/news/canada/pot-activists-marc-and-jodie-emery-plead-guilty-to-drug-related-charges|title=Pot activists Marc and Jodie Emery plead guilty to drug-related charges|last=Casey|first=Liam|date=18 December 2017|work=[[National Post]]|agency=[[The Canadian Press]]}}</ref> Drug-related charges were laid against three others who were also subsequently convicted.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n[[Toronto Police Service|Toronto Police]] had told the media that the unlicensed cannabis dispensaries are linked to \"high-level drug traffickers ... often tied to organized crime, given the amount of marijuana sold\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Brait |first=Ellen |date=10 March 2017 |title='Prince and Princess of Pot' released on bail |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2017/03/09/prince-and-princess-of-pot-reportedly-arrested-at-toronto-airport.html | work=Toronto Star |location=Toronto |access-date=13 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[First Nations]] chiefs attending the [[Assembly of First Nations]] widely agreed that the distribution of cannabis on [[List of Indian reserves in Canada|reserve lands]] should be governed by First Nations governments, and not provincial legislation.<ref>{{cite news |title=First Nations demand control over cannabis sales |newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]] |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/first-nations-want-to-set-own-rules-for-cannabis-sales/article37231232/ |first=Gloria |last=Galloway |date=7 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nImmediately after legalization, licensed growers often had difficulty accessing financial services. [[Alterna Savings]] and [[Alterna Bank]] were among the first financial institutions to make loans to businesses focusing on cannabis in Canada, providing primary banking services for approximately two-thirds of the hundred licensed growers in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Alexander |first1=Doug |title=Alterna CEO embraced weed business when nobody else would |url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2018/04/06/alterna-ceo-embraced-weed-business-when-nobody-else-would.html |accessdate=2 May 2019 |work=Toronto Star |date=6 April 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Final legalization===\n{{see|An Act to amend the Criminal Code (offences relating to conveyances)}}\n[[File:Canadian_House_of_Commons_-_Bill_C-45_(Cannabis_Act)_-_Voting_Results_by_MP_(Simple_Map).svg|thumb|250px|Map showing which MP's voted in favour (green), against (red), abstained (grey) or whether the seat was vacant (black).]]\n\nAfter the House of Commons passed Bill C-45, it was sent to the Senate. On 1 June 2018, the Senate passed an amendment to C-45 outlawing cannabis \"brand-stretching\". The amendment, which passed 34\u201328 in the Senate,<ref name=dnapvp /> would have outlawed the sale and display of cannabis-related merchandise once legalized.<ref name=\"dnapvp\">{{cite web|url=https://ipolitics.ca/2018/06/01/senate-votes-to-ban-company-branded-cannabis-swag/|title=Senate votes to ban company branded cannabis swag|last=Duggan|first=Kyle|date=1 June 2018|website=iPolitics}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/marijuana-bill-faces-critical-vote-at-last-step-ahead-of-legalization-1.3958662|title=Timeline of key events in marijuana bill's passage through Parliament|last=Aiello|first=Rachel|date=4 June 2018|work=[[CTV News]]}}</ref> The amendment was rejected by the House of Commons.<ref>{{cite web |title=Motions Respecting Senate Amendments to Bills |publisher=[[Parliament of Canada]] |url=http://www.ourcommons.ca/DocumentViewer/en/42-1/house/sitting-316/order-notice/page-13 |date=18 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 June 2018, the Senate finally passed the bill, without the rejected amendment, and the Prime Minister announced the effective legalization date as 17 October 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4285946/marijuana-legal-date-october-17-canada-trudeau-confirms/|title=Marijuana to be legal in Canada starting October 17, Trudeau confirms|last=Scott|first=Monique|date=20 June 2018|work=[[Global News]]|access-date=}}</ref> Canada became the second nation (after [[Uruguay]]) to legalize the drug.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\nAs expected, the use of cannabis for recreational purposes became legal across the country on 17 October 2018, under the ''Cannabis Act'' which \"creates a legal and regulatory framework for controlling the production, distribution, sale and possession of cannabis in Canada\", according to a Government of Canada web site.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.canada.ca/en/health-canada/news/2018/06/backgrounder-the-cannabis-act-the-facts.html |title=The Cannabis Act: The Facts |date=20 June 2018 |website=Health Canada |publisher=Government of Canada |access-date=27 October 2018}}</ref> Persons aged 18 or older can possess up to 30 grams of dried or \"equivalent non-dried form\" in public. Adults are also allowed to make cannabis-infused food and drinks \"as long as organic solvents are not used to create concentrated products\". Each household is allowed to grow up to four cannabis plants from \"licensed seed or seedlings\", although Quebec and Manitoba chose to be excluded from this aspect of the legislation.\n\nEach province set its own procedures for retail sales, and these vary as to ownership or retail outlets (by the provincial government or private enterprise), but all include an option for on-line sales. Since marijuana is illegal in the U.S. per federal legislation, the government warned that \"previous use of cannabis, or any substance prohibited by U.S. federal laws, could mean that you are denied entry to the U.S.\" Canadians travelling within the country (but not internationally) are allowed to carry up to 30 grams of cannabis. Naturally, driving under the influence of drugs remained illegal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4559085/marijuana-legalization-canada-midnight/ |title=Marijuana is legal everywhere across Canada now |date=17 October 2018 |website=Inside Halton |publisher=Metroland News |access-date=27 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/marijuana-faq-legalization-need-to-know-1.4862207 |title=Cannabis is legal in Canada \u2013 here's what you need to know |date=17 October 2018 |website=CBC News |publisher=CBC |access-date=27 October 2018}}</ref> It was announced that on 1 May 2019, Canada would introduce excise tax on all products containing THC, and introduce three new product classes for recreational sale: cannabis edibles, cannabis extracts, and cannabis topicals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://extractmag.com/cannabis-edibles-extracts-and-topicals-thc-excise-tax-coming-to-canadians-may-1-2019/ |title=Cannabis Edibles, Extracts and Topicals & THC Excise Tax Coming To Canadians May 1, 2019 |date=19 March 2019 |website=Extract Magazine |publisher=Jordan Alexander |access-date=26 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs of August 2019, the federal government still prohibited the sale of edibles, such as cookies. Such products were expected to become legal in October 2019, but with restrictions. The intent was to not allow any products that would be \"appealing to young persons\", probably including the colourful \"gummies\" candy which was very popular on the black market.<ref>https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/companies-push-ahead-pot-gummy-plans-hazy-regulations-1.5259374, Companies push ahead on pot gummy plans despite hazy regulations</ref>\n\n== Public opinion, 1997\u20132016 ==\n[[File:Canada - Cannabis Day, Marijuana Party 2014 @ Art Gallery (14370054340).jpg|right|thumb|\"Canada/Cannabis Day\", 2014]]\nSince 1997, public opinion polls have found an increasing majority of Canadians agree with the statement, \"Smoking marijuana should not be a criminal offence\".<ref name=\"The Fraser Institute 1997\">{{cite web|url=http://oldfraser.lexi.net/publications/books/drug_papers/UDSavas.pdf|title=Public Opinion and Illicit Drugs \u2013 Canadian Attitudes towards Decriminalizing the Use of Marijuana|publisher=The Fraser Institute|date=April 2001|accessdate=23 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130629082437/http://oldfraser.lexi.net/publications/books/drug_papers/UDSavas.pdf|archive-date=29 June 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> In June 2016, a national poll conducted by [[Nanos Research]] showed that 7 in 10 Canadians were in favour of legalization.<ref name=\"Nanos Poll 2016\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/7-in-10-canadians-support-marijuana-legalization-nanos-poll-1.2968953|title=7 in 10 Canadians support marijuana legalization: Nanos poll|last=Tahirali|first=Jesse|date=30 June 2016|work=[[CTV News]]|accessdate=11 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nBy 2006, a high percentage of the population was using cannabis,<ref name=\"Martel2006\">{{cite book|author=Marcel Martel|title=Not This Time: Canadians, Public Policy, and the Marijuana Question, 1961\u20131975|url=https://archive.org/details/notthistimecanad0000mart|url-access=registration|year=2006|publisher=University of Toronto Press, Scholarly Publishing Division|isbn=978-1-4426-5885-1|page=[https://archive.org/details/notthistimecanad0000mart/page/28 28]}}</ref> in spite of the risk of police charges for possession, and especially for selling it without the required licence, according to statistics gathered by the [[Centre for Addiction and Mental Health]] (CAMH). Nearly half (44%) of Canadians admit to trying it at least once; no statistics were provided as to the percentage who use it frequently. The CAMH report also indicates that by the last year of high school, nearly half (46%) of Ontario students admit to having used marijuana in the past year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.camh.ca/en/hospital/health_information/a_z_mental_health_and_addiction_information/marijuana/Pages/about_marijuana.aspx |title=About Marijuana |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2012 |website=CAMH |publisher=CAMH |access-date=2 December 2016}}</ref> The CAMH discussion includes warnings about the negative [[effects of cannabis]]. Other groups also warn about the risk, including the [[Canadian Automobile Association]] whose 2016 poll indicated, \"Almost two-thirds of Canadians are concerned that roads will become more dangerous [due to impairment by the drug] with the legalization of marijuana\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bcaa.com/learning-centre/bcaa-newsroom/news-releases/2016-11-14-caa-media-release-roads-unsafe-marijuana-legalized |title=Canadians Worry Roads Will Be Unsafe When Marijuana Legalized |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=14 November 2016 |website=BCAA |publisher=BCAA |access-date=2 December 2016 |quote=There are a lot of misconceptions out there that marijuana doesn't affect your driving, or even worse, it makes you a better driver ... There needs to be significant resources devoted to educating the public in the run-up to \u2013 and after \u2013 marijuana is legalized.}}</ref> An October 2016 national poll by Forum suggests that about five million adult Canadians now use cannabis at least once a month; this is expected to increase by 19 percent after marijuana is legalized.<ref name=\":2\" /> [[Canaccord Genuity]] analysts Matt Bottomley and Neil Maruoka released a research note with a more moderate estimate of the number of users. They predicted that approximately 3.8 million persons will be recreational users (presumably on a frequent basis) by 2021.<ref name=\"Skerrit\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/investment-ideas/marijuana-producer-jumps-356-in-canadas-investor-pot-frenzy/article33100749/|title=Marijuana producer jumps 356% as Canada's investor pot frenzy intensifies|last=Skerrit|first=Jen|date=30 November 2016|newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]]|access-date=2 December 2016|agency=[[Bloomberg News]]|last2=Lam|first2=Eric}}</ref> A report by Canada's [[Parliamentary Budget Officer]] (PBO) is more bullish, estimating that by 2021 some 5.2 million adults may be users.<ref name=\"Cullen\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/marijuana-parliamentary-budget-officer-revenues-1.3830593|title=Legal marijuana could raise federal cash \u2013 but not right away, PBO says|last=Cullen|first=Catherine|date=1 November 2016|work=[[CBC News]]|access-date=4 December 2016|quote=In the first three years, it expects the number of cannabis users aged 15 and over to grow by more than half a million, rising to an estimated 5.2 million in 2021.}}</ref>\n\n== Cannabis as a commodity ==\n[[File:Cannabis Indica 01.jpg|Example of a container and the recreational cannabis purchase in Canada.|thumb]] [[File:Emballage de cannabis Indica 03.jpg|Mandatory cannabis excise stamp on recreational cannabis sold in Canada.|thumb]]\nGrowers that currently produce marijuana are licensed by Health Canada under the [[Access to Cannabis for Medical Purposes Regulations (ACMPR).|Access to Cannabis for Medical Purposes Regulations]] (ACMPR). As of late 2016, there were 36 authorized producers across the country in Health Canada's list. Sales were allowed only by mail order, but by late 2017, some major retailers had applied for a change in the rules to allow them to also sell the product.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2017/11/13/shoppers-drug-mart-seeks-medical-marijuana-brand-manager.html|title=Shoppers Drug Mart seeks medical marijuana brand manager|last=Ligaya|first=Armina|date=13 November 2017|work=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref> By 21 December 2017, 82 licences had been issued<ref>{{cite news|url=https://business.financialpost.com/investing/marijuana-stocks-see-big-gains-as-trading-resumes-after-christmas-break|title=Marijuana stocks surge again as trading resumes after Christmas break|last=Zochodne|first=Geoff|date=27 December 2017|work=[[Financial Post]]}}</ref> under the ACMPR, but not all of the producers had been licensed to begin selling medical marijuana. The vast majority of these companies were located in Ontario.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/health-canada/services/drugs-health-products/medical-use-marijuana/licensed-producers/authorized-licensed-producers-medical-purposes.html|title=Authorized Licensed Producers of Cannabis for Medical Purposes \u2013 Canada.ca|first=Health|last=Canada|website=canada.ca}}</ref> At that time, no licences had been issued yet for producing recreational cannabis; the producers already licensed were hoping to be added to that list after it is created.<ref name=\"financialpost.com\">{{cite news|url=https://business.financialpost.com/investing/medical-marijuana-producers-bristle-at-ontarios-planned-monopoly-on-recreational-cannabis-sales|title=Medical marijuana producers bristle at Ontario's planned monopoly on recreational cannabis sales|last=Zochodne|first=Geoff|date=11 September 2017|work=[[Financial Post]]}}</ref> Between 1 February and early April 2018, some 89 additional applicants were approved as cannabis growers by Health Canada; at the time, the agency was considering the merits of another 244 applications.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-04-05/marijuana-millionaires-riding-canada-s-legalization-wave|title=Marijuana Millionaires Ride Canada's Legalization Wave|last=Skerritt|first=Jen|date=5 April 2018|work=[[Bloomberg News]]}}</ref>\n\nStatistics indicate that, as of September 2016, nearly 100,000 Canadians had bought medical marijuana legally, a significant increase over the 30,537 in September 2015, presumably since it is becoming a mainstream drug and since supplies are becoming more readily available.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/number-of-canadians-buying-legal-medical-marijuana-triples-in-just-one-year|title=Number of Canadians buying legal medical marijuana triples in just one year|last=Miller|first=Jacquie|date=12 December 2016|newspaper=[[Ottawa Citizen]]|access-date=14 December 2016}}</ref> According to a [[StatsCan]] estimate, Canadians may have spent roughly CAD$6.2 billion (US$4.8 billion) on marijuana in 2015, although the agency admits that there is no scientific method of accurately measuring illegal consumption.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloombergquint.com/business/2017/12/18/marijuana-use-may-have-hit-c-6-2-bln-before-canada-legalization|title=Canadians Consume Almost as Much Weed as Wine, Report Shows|last=Quinn|first=Greg|date=19 December 2017|work=[[BloombergQuint]]}}</ref>\n\nThe report by the Task Force on Marijuana Legalization and Regulation had recommended that recreational cannabis growers should be licensed at a federal level, separately from the producers of medical marijuana. The expert panel also recommended that the process ensure competition by licensing both large and small producers. While licensing should be federal, each of the provinces should be allowed to determine how and where the product will be sold.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://in.reuters.com/article/us-canada-marijuana-idINKBN1421UG|title=Canada should regulate recreational pot production: panel|last=Schnurr|first=Leah|date=13 December 2016|access-date=13 December 2016|agency=[[Reuters]]|last2=Ljunggren|first2=David|quote=The Canadian government should regulate the production of cannabis when it is legalized for recreational use while the provinces should be allowed to determine how it is sold, an official panel recommended on Tuesday.}}</ref>\n\nAfter the plans for legalization<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-12-20/trudeau-sees-pot-legalized-by-summer-as-law-sits-in-senate|title=Trudeau Sees Pot Legalized by Summer as Law Sits in Senate|last=Wingrove|first=Josh|date=20 December 2017|work=[[Bloomberg News]]}}</ref> became well-publicized, industry analysts reported that some of the producers who had been licensed for medical marijuana, including [[Aurora Cannabis]], were already increasing the capacity of their operations for future sales to the distributors of recreational cannabis.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/marijuana-businesses-legalization-date-1.4042599|title=Marijuana industry gets boost from legalization target date|last=Israel|first=Solomon|date=28 March 2017|work=[[CBC News]]|access-date=28 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nA report in late November 2017 by [[Ernst & Young]] suggested that there would be mergers, leaving fewer players in this industry. \"Many believe that consolidation is inevitable, leaving a few large players post-legalization.\" Also in late 2017, [[Deloitte]] predicted that the recreational cannabis market would be worth close to $23 billion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/marijuana-cannabis-mergers-pot-canada-1.4415933|title=Merger madness: Canada's marijuana industry enters consolidation phase|last=Armstrong|first=Peter|date=27 November 2017|work=[[CBC News]]}}</ref> Lately, US Alcohol companies have been showing interest in the Cannabis business in Canada.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/thomaspellechia/2018/09/13/canadas-cannabis-future-attracts-u-s-alcohol-companies/#5039255ec40c|title=Canada's Cannabis Future Attracts U.S. Alcohol Companies|last=Pellechia|first=Thomas|work=Forbes|access-date=30 September 2018|language=en}}</ref> US Cannabis producers are afraid that Canada is going to be the prime dominator in the market.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2018/09/29/canadian-cannabis-dominate-industry_a_23545796/|title=U.S. Cannabis Producers Fear Canada Will 'Dominate The Industry'|date=29 September 2018|work=HuffPost Canada|access-date=30 September 2018|language=en-CA}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 October 2019, alternative cannabis products such as drinks, edibles, and topicals will become legal for production,<ref>{{cite news |title=Cannabis edibles available for sale legally in mid-December|first=Hannah |last=Thibedeau |date=24 June 2019 |website=CBC News |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/marijuana-cannabis-edibles-extracts-vaping-1.5174844 |accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref> and are expected to be available for sale two months later. [[Deloitte]] has predicted that the alternative cannabis product market will be worth close to $2.7 billion.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sokic |first1=Nicholas |title=Deloitte pegs market for alternative cannabis products at $2.7 billion |url=https://business.financialpost.com/cannabis/deloitte-pegs-market-for-alternative-cannabis-products-at-2-7-billion |work=Financial Post |date=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nDue to illegality of cannabis [[Cannabis in the United States|federally in the United States]], crossing the international border from Canada into the United States while carrying cannabis is still illegal. Past consumption of cannabis can also lead to a permanent ban on entry to the U.S.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tasker |first1=John Paul |title=Cannabis and the border: what pot-smoking Canadians need to know |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/tasker-smoke-pot-us-border-oct-17-1.4865696 |accessdate=3 March 2019 |work=CBC |date=16 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Major producers (2018)===\nAs of late October 2018, the largest of the producers licensed by the federal government was [[Canopy Growth Corporation]] of [[Smiths Falls, Ontario]]; the company was renamed from Tweed Marijuana Inc. in September 2015<ref>{{cite news|url=https://business.financialpost.com/news/agriculture/tweed-marijuana-renames-itself-canopy-growth-corp-as-it-charts-growth-path-at-agm|title=Tweed Marijuana renames itself Canopy Growth Corp as it charts growth path at AGM|last=Koven|first=Peter|date=17 September 2016|newspaper=[[Financial Post]]|access-date=2 December 2016}}</ref> after it purchased competitor Bedrocan. Subsequent acquisitions for this corporation included Vert Medical, the German cannabis distributor MedCann, and a majority interest in Quebec's Groupe H.E.M.P.CA Inc. In early December 2016, Canopy announced a friendly takeover bid of another Canadian producer, Mettrum Health (CVE:MT), in anticipation of an expanding market after marijuana is legalized for recreational purposes in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mettrum.com/investors/news-releases/canopy-growth-and-mettrum-announce-respective-shareholder-approvals-of-the-plan-of-arrangement/ |title=Canopy Growth and Mettrum Announce Respective Shareholder Approvals of the Plan of Arrangement |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=27 January 2017 |website=Mettrum |access-date=15 February 2017}}</ref> In addition to sales in the domestic market, Canopy Growth began selling medical cannabis products in Germany and Brazil in 2016. The company was described as \"one of the world's \u2013 and Canada's first \u2013 premier exporters of marijuana\" by the ''[[Financial Post]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://business.financialpost.com/midas-letter/canopy-takes-over-mettrum-heres-who-might-be-next-in-its-sights|title=Canopy takes over Mettrum, here's who might be next in its sights|last=MidasLetter|date=1 December 2016|newspaper=[[Financial Post]]|access-date=2 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nCanopy Growth's patient base increased by approximately 260 percent and revenue by about 180 percent in the calendar year 2016 vs. 2015. The increase would have been even greater, but the company had difficulty maintaining adequate stock in some high-demand categories such as mid-to-high THC level products and oils. A report by the ''Financial Post'' indicated that inventory shortfalls have been a problem for many of Canada's licensed medical marijuana producers; this could worsen after recreational marijuana is legalized. When the year end report was released, Canopy Growth's share price fell seven percent to $12.09 on the [[Toronto Stock Exchange]] (ticker WEED).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://business.financialpost.com/commodities/agriculture/canopy-growth-corp-almost-triples-revenue-as-number-of-patients-soars|title=Canopy Growth Corp almost triples revenue as number of patients soars|last=Freeman|first=Sunny|date=14 February 2017|newspaper=[[Financial Post]]|access-date=14 February 2017}}</ref> The December 2016 year end report indicated a profit for the first time in the company's history (3 million in net income). Previously, Canopy Growth had been operating at a loss ($3.3 million in 2015, for example), partly because it was using funds to acquire competitors in preparation for significantly increased cannabis demand by the recreational use market expected to commence in early 2018. In early December 2016, [[Reuters]]' survey of four market analysts had indicated a consensus rating of Buy in early December 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/markets/stocks/news/?q=CGC-T|title=Canopy Growth Corp|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|access-date=2 December 2016|quote=Canopy Growth Corporation, formerly Tweed Marijuana Inc., is a diversified cannabis company.}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, [[Constellation Brands]] announced that it would invest an additional US$4 billion in Canopy Growth Corporation in advance of the legalization of recreational marijuana. The investment will increase its share in the company from 9.9% to 38%. Canopy Growth president Bruce Linton said the additional funds would be used for international expansion and that future marketing plans included products such as cannabis-infused beverages and sleep aids.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/08/15/corona-maker-constellation-ups-bet-on-cannabis-with-4-billion-investm.html|title=Corona beer maker Constellation ups bet on cannabis with $4 billion investment in Canopy Growth|last=Sheetz|first=Michael|date=15 August 2017|work=[[CNBC]]|accessdate=10 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://business.financialpost.com/cannabis/constellation-brands-spending-5-billion-to-increase-stake-in-canopy-growth|title='This is rocket fuel': Constellation Brands spending $5 billion to boost stake in Canopy Growth|last=Pfanner|first=Eric|date=15 August 2017|work=[[Financial Post]]|accessdate=10 August 2017|agency=[[Bloomberg News]]|last2=Owram|first2=Kristine|last3=Skerritt|first3=Jen}}</ref> After the Constellation deal was announced, the market value of Canopy Growth rose to nearly US$12 billion,<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news|url=https://business.financialpost.com/cannabis/with-5-billion-constellation-deal-canopy-growth-is-emerging-as-the-google-of-pot|title=With $5-billion Constellation deal, Canopy Growth is emerging as the Google of pot|last=Owram|first=Kristine|date=22 August 2018|work=[[Financial Post]]|accessdate=23 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/investing/stock/cgc|title=Canopy Growth \n|work=Market Watch|accessdate=23 August 2018|quote=Market Cap $11.19B}}</ref> \nroughly $3.7 billion greater than that of the closest competitor [[Aurora Cannabis]].<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nEarlier in 2018, the second largest producer, Aurora Cannabis, bought competitor [[CanniMed]] in advance of the anticipated growth in the market and announced a plan to acquire MedReleaf.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/aurora-medreleaf-pot-deal-1.4661629|title=Aurora buys MedReleaf to cement status as world's biggest cannabis company \u2013 CBC News|last=Evans|first=Pete|date=14 May 2018|work=[[CBC News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://business.financialpost.com/cannabis/our-eyes-are-on-the-global-market-aurora-acquires-medreleaf-in-largest-cannabis-deal-yet|title='Our eyes are on the global market': Aurora acquires MedReleaf in largest cannabis deal yet|last=Rendell|first=Mark|date=5 June 2018|work=[[Financial Post]]}}</ref> It would have distribution agreements in a number of countries, including Germany, Italy, Brazil, and Australia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/edmonton/2018/05/14/edmontons-aurora-cannabis-buys-medreleaf-for-32-billion-becoming-largest-cannabis-producer-in-the-world.html|title=Edmonton's Aurora Cannabis buys MedReleaf for $3.2-billion, becoming 'largest cannabis producer in the world'|last=Maimann|first=Kevin|date=14 May 2018|work=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref>\n\nBy late September, Tilray, Inc. of [[Nanaimo]], a subsidiary of [[Privateer Holdings]] had reached a market capitalization about US$10 billion making it the third largest cannabis company in the world, after Canopy and Aurora.<ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/09/24/tilray-shares-wipe-out-gains-from-last-weeks-wild-ride.html |title=Pot stock Tilray tumbles, completely wiping out gains from last week's wild surge|publisher=CNBC|date=24 September 2018 |accessdate=26 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019 sales volume===\nAn October 2019 report stated that total cannabis sales for the first seven months of the year were only C$524 million when C$4.34 billion (US$3.29 billion) was forecast a year ago.<ref name=\"owram\">{{cite news|author=Kristine Owram|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-10-15/one-year-in-legal-canadian-pot-fails-to-match-the-hype|title=One Year In, Legal Canadian Pot Fails to Match the Hype|date=15 October 2019|work=Bloomberg News|accessdate=15 October 2019}}</ref> Sales were modest because of the limited number of retail operations in Ontario and Quebec where some 23 million people resided; each province had only 25 outlets, as of October 2019.<ref name=owram/> The relatively high cost of the legal product \u2013 almost double that of the [[black market]] \u2013 and the limited types of product (dried flower and oils) also worked against retail sales.<ref name=owram/> In late 2019, more stores were being opened and a wider range of legal cannabis was becoming available, including edibles, topicals, and [[vaping]] products.<ref name=owram/>\n\nProfitability was a problem however, according to a report in early November 2019 which stated, \"pot stocks down nearly 60 per cent since March highs\". This was leading companies to sell off real estate holdings as a method of raising capital to finance expansion. \n<ref>{{cite web |url=https://business.financialpost.com/real-estate/property-post/pot-companies-shed-real-estate-amid-dearth-of-financing-options |title=https://business.financialpost.com/real-estate/property-post/pot-companies-shed-real-estate-amid-dearth-of-financing-options|date=6 November 2019 |work=Financial Post|access-date=8 November 2019 |quote=Sale-leaseback transactions have stepped in to fill the void, becoming a key financial lifeline for an industry that needs capital to fund expansion.}}</ref>\n\n===Competing with the black market===\nA report in October 2019 by [[Bloomberg News]] painted a bleak picture of the legal cannabis industry. Because of the relatively few retail outlets, especially in Ontario, and the high retail prices, the black market remained persistent. An independent cannabis research firm estimated that the black market accounted for 86% of cannabis sales. On average, on a Canada-wide basis, legal cannabis was selling for about $10.23 per gram versus $5.59 found on the black market according to StatsCan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bnnbloomberg.ca/cannabis-gold-rush-falling-short-amid-lure-of-cheaper-black-market-pot-say-analysts-1.1329064|title=Cannabis 'gold rush' falling short amid cheap black market: Analysts - Article|first=David|last=George-Cosh|date=9 October 2019|website=BNN}}</ref>\n\nOntario, at least, planned to take steps in 2020 to increase the number of retail licenses issued per month to increase the availability of legal cannabis, in order to combat the illicit market.<ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/cannibis-store-cap-1.5394662 Ontario removing cap on number of pot shops, opening up market for retailers]</ref>\n\n===Craft cannabis===\nUnder the ''Cannabis Act'' passed in 2018, only producers licensed by the government are allowed to grow the product. As of early October 2018, there were at least 117 such licensed producers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/legal-cannabis-shortage-looms-1.4845816 |title=Don't delete your dealer's number yet \u2013 legal cannabis shortage looms |publisher =CBC News |access-date=27 October 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAlthough consolidation of the cannabis market in Canada is expected to the point where \"a handful of companies will control the majority of the market\",<ref>{{cite news |last=Wood|first=David|date=19 October 2018|title=The cannabis industry can expect more growth \u2013 and consolidation|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/cannabis/article-the-cannabis-industry-can-expect-more-growth-and-consolidation/ |work=Globe and Mail |access-date=21 October 2018 }}</ref> many claim that there is an important need for smaller craft cannabis producers that are \"more able to adapt to consumer demand\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Campbell|first=Lisa|date=1 July 2018|title=New regulations may spark Canada's craft cannabis revolution|url=https://www.straight.com/cannabis/1097161/new-regulations-may-spark-canadas-craft-cannabis-revolution#|work=The Georgia Straight|access-date=21 October 2018 }}</ref> The craft cannabis industry has been compared to the craft beer industry<ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite web |url=https://licensedproducerscanada.ca/faq/what-is-a-health-canada-licensed-producer|title=Will Craft Cannabis Growers in Canada Succeed Like Craft Brewers?|website=Licensed Producers Canada|access-date=21 October 2018}}</ref> \u2013 smaller producers who are able to experiment more and provide a wider variety to the larger companies, which will likely try to please as many consumers as possible. However, the difference is that the relatively new rise of craft brewers in a mature market is different than craft cannabis starting at the same time as larger producers (for recreational cannabis). This will give larger producers the edge in the short term since those companies have more money.<ref>{{cite news |last=Reid|first=Sarah|date=15 November 2017|title=Small pot producers' plans go up in smoke|url=https://tvo.org/article/current-affairs/small-pot-producers-plans-go-up-in-smoke|work=TVO |access-date=21 October 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe expected buy-in for craft cannabis producers is perhaps slightly higher than craft brewers,<ref name=\"auto5\"/> but there are other barriers to launching a craft cannabis company including the ability to market product. Cannabis marketing will be closer to tobacco marketing (which is prohibited in Canada with few limited exceptions<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tobaccocontrollaws.org/legislation/country/canada/summary|title= Legislation by Country: Canada|website=Tobacco Control Laws|access-date=21 October 2018}}</ref>) cannabis will be sold in plain packaging and traditional advertising such as TV commercials will be prohibited.<ref>{{cite news |last=Delacourt|first=Susan|date=23 June 2017|title=Canadian pot ads? Think beer ads. Then think again: Delacourt|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/insight/2017/06/23/canadian-pot-ads-think-beer-ads-then-think-again-delacourt.html|work=Toronto Star|access-date=21 October 2018 }}</ref> They will likely not even be able to mention things that could be important to the consumer such as where it's grown (i.e., \"buy local\") and if it's organic.<ref>{{cite news |date=19 May 2017|title=Craft cannabis growers in B.C. sound alarm over survival of sector|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/cannabis-growers-bc-sound-alarm-over-sector-1.4670742|work=Canadian Press|access-date=21 October 2018 }}</ref>\n\nFurther, simply selling their product may be difficult. The supply chain is still not entirely clear as it is in the beer industry, but there are ways for craft cannabis producers to sell their product through selling to other micro-processors \u2013 and potentially larger producers \u2013 or applying for a micro-processing licence themselves.<ref name=\"auto6\">{{cite news |last=Efron|first=Sarah|date=22 June 2018|title=Craft cannabis growers say better bud will be key to thriving in the legal market|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/business/small-business/growth/article-craft-cannabis-growers-say-better-bud-will-be-key-to-thriving-in-the/|work=Globe and Mail|access-date=21 October 2018 }}</ref> As of the legalization date, consumers cannot sample or purchase product directly from a craft cannabis producer's storefront as you can with craft beer or buy cannabis from a stall on the side of the road as you might from a farmer. However, [[British Columbia]]'s Public Safety Minister Mike Farnsworth said that the province wouldn't rule out farmers selling direct to consumer.<ref>{{cite news |date=19 May 2017|title=Craft cannabis growers in B.C. sound alarm over survival of sector|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/cannabis-growers-bc-sound-alarm-over-sector-1.4670742|work=CBC|access-date=22 October 2018 }}</ref>\n\nStill, most craft cannabis producers are optimistic. One craft cannabis producer told ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' that \"I think there is a real opportunity there for small independents.\"<ref name=\"auto6\"/> Craft cannabis producers are seen by some as the \"artisans of the industry\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Ross|first=Andrea|date=24 June 2018|title=First comes legal cannabis. Then, say industry insiders, will come the artisan stuff|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/alberta-cannabis-industry-craft-growers-1.4758573|work=CBC|access-date=22 October 2018 }}</ref> who will experiment with strains, increase variety, and produce a quality product that it can sell at a premium.<ref name=\"auto5\"/>\n\n===Stock market volatility===\n{{overly detailed|date=November 2019}}\nAt times in 2016, and in 2017, the stock prices of some producers increased significantly as retail investors became more bullish on this segment of the market but then dropped at a later date.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/inside-the-market/over-50-in-3-days-why-investors-have-pushed-aurora-shares-to-new-highs/article36971073/|title=Up 60% in three days: Why investors are euphoric over Aurora Cannabis shares|last=Bouw|first=Brenda|date=14 November 2017|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref> Between September and mid-November 2017, the typical stock cannabis producer's value increased by 54%, according to Vahan Ajamian of Beacon Securities Ltd. The share price of Canopy Growth, for example, more than doubled in price during the fall of the year, but declined in mid-November while others, such as Aurora Cannabis, increased at the same time during another volatile period.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baystreet.ca/etfs/206/Jump-Into-the-Red-Hot-Cannabis-Market-With-This-ETF|title=Jump into the Red Hot Cannabis Market With This ETF|last=O'Callaghan|first=Ambrose|date=8 November 2017|website=Baystreet.ca}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/canopy-growth-reports-third-quarter-loss-revenue-jumps/article36970222/|title=Canopy Growth's second-quarter loss dampens marijuana stock rally|last=Pellegrini|first=Christina|date=14 November 2017|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> At the time, analysts could not predict the long-term outcome for any company.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-11-14/amid-marijuana-boom-cost-data-leave-analysts-dazed-and-confused|title=Amid Marijuana Boom, Costs Leave Analysts Dazed and Confused|last=Skerritt|first=Jen|date=14 November 2017|website=[[Bloomberg News]]}}</ref> A report by [[Investopedia]] in November said that most cannabis stocks \"can be labeled as penny stocks, so any investment may carry a significantly higher risk component.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investopedia.com/investing/10-canadian-marijuana-stocks/|title=10 Canadian Marijuana Stocks for Your Portfolio|last=Krishna|first=Mrinalini|date=3 August 2018|website=[[Investopedia]]}}</ref>\n\nMarket analysts Matt Bottomley and Neil Maruoka of Canaccord Genuity believe that approximately 3.8 million persons will be recreational users (presumably on a frequent basis) by 2021 with a potential for $6 billion in sales.<ref name=\"Skerrit\"/> These analysts predicted that after legalization, there may be a \"shortfall of supply in the near term\", which is likely to increase the product's selling price. Their prediction was based on the government's strict standards, which have resulted in few producers becoming licensed under the current system.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2016/11/30/canada-marijuana-shortage-legalization_n_13336348.html|title=Canada May Face Marijuana Shortage When It's Legalized: Canaccord|last=Tencer|first=Daniel|date=1 December 2016|website=[[Huffington Post]]|access-date=2 December 2016|quote=Canada's system for licensing marijuana producers is so tough that there likely won't be enough producers to meet demand when the federal Liberals legalize the herb}}</ref>\n\nSome industry observers warned that \"speculation and investor frenzy are fuelling many of the gains\". Other observers pointed out that marijuana company values are high but said that \"the players have real products with real sales that are growing, unlike the many dot-com firms that fed that bubble.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Southwick |first=Reid |date=27 January 2017 |title=Investors dive into marijuana stocks, raising concerns about green bubble |url=https://calgaryherald.com/business/local-business/investors-dive-into-marijuana-stocks-raising-concerns-about-green-bubble |newspaper=Herald |location=Calgary |access-date=15 February 2017}}</ref> Some market analysts voiced concern about the long-term retail price of recreational marijuana; they predict that it will decline over time after legalization because of competition and bulk sales to provincial governments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.financialpost.com/commodities/agriculture/amid-marijuana-boom-cost-data-leave-analysts-dazed-and-confused|title='A mad green rush': As marijuana booms, analysts still hazy on impact of Canadian legalization on costs|date=14 November 2017}}</ref> The probability of reducing prices as producers' costs decline due to economies of scale was confirmed by the head of the federal-provincial task force in late 2017. The government also intends to keep the net cost to the consumer adequately low so as to virtually eliminate the need for an illegal market but \"not so low as to create an incentive for increased use\".<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nCertain investment counsellors also warned clients that marijuana stocks are very risky.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bnnbloomberg.ca/video/investing-in-marijuana-stocks-a-tough-gamble-portfolio-manager~1249335|title=Video - BNN - Business News Network|website=BNN}}</ref> According to Barry Schwartz, chief investment officer at Baskin Wealth Management in Toronto, \"It's not the type of investment we'd ever make\" adding that he would advise anyone who asks about investing in this sector, \"don't do it\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Gibillini |first=Nicole |date=1 December 2016 |title='Don't do it': Marijuana stocks 'very risky' for investors, money manager says |url=http://www.bnn.ca/don-t-do-it-marijuana-stocks-very-risky-for-investors-money-manager-warns-1.621309 |publisher=BNN/Bell Media |location=Toronto |access-date=2 December 2016}}</ref> In spite of the significant increases in the stock prices of several cannabis producers in early November 2017, few institutional investors were buying such shares because of the uncertainty as to which would succeed and which would fail.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bnnbloomberg.ca/commodities/video/cannabis-not-a-market-most-institutional-investors-want-to-get-into-says-portfolio-s-levine~1257277|title=Video|website=BNN}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, business columnist David Olive of the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' strongly recommended against investing in this industry. His rationale includes these aspects: there are too many producers for the small Canadian market (\"close to 100 players\"), retail prices will drop significantly, reducing margins, and the expense ratio is excessively high, so most companies will not be profitable. \"Only the most risk-tolerant and speculative-minded investors should go anywhere near it,\" he warned.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2017/11/17/6-reasons-an-investment-in-the-pot-industry-will-likely-go-up-in-smoke-olive.html|title=6 reasons an investment in the pot industry will likely go up in smoke: Olive|first=David|last=Olive|date=17 November 2017|work=Toronto Star}}</ref>\n\nThe promise of legalization boosted the share price of marijuana growers on the Toronto Stock Exchange in November and December 2017.<ref>[http://mjinews.com/marijuana-index-gains-continue-pot-stock/ \"Marijuana Index Gains Continue As Pot Stocks Anticipate Prohibition Repeal\"], ''MJI News''.</ref> A market analyst explained that the confidence was based on the fact that legal marijuana will not be more expensive, with tax included, than the black market product; this should ensure a sizeable market for producers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bnn.ca/marijuana-stocks-rally-following-ottawa-s-proposed-dollar-a-gram-tax-1.912096|title=Marijuana stocks rally following Ottawa's proposed dollar-a-gram tax|date=10 November 2017|publisher=BNN}}</ref> Advertising will probably be used to boost sales. The federal task force had recommended that restrictions on ad content should be similar to those for tobacco ads, extremely stringent. The cannabis producers' lobby group, however, was proposing the gentler restrictions that apply to alcohol producers: not to appeal to youth and to promote only the brand, not the recreational use of the product.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/business/marijuana-producers-want-advertising-rules-akin-to-alcohol-not-cigarettes-1.3674405|title=Marijuana producers want advertising rules akin to alcohol, not cigarettes|date=12 November 2017|publisher=CTV News}}</ref>\n\nAs the stock markets approached the year-end closing in 2017, the price of major cannabis stocks surged but [[Bloomberg News]] reported that \"some analysts are skeptical about demand projections, and betting against the stocks is difficult to do\" because there was \"almost no stock left to short, and some investors who have taken short positions in the market have lost money\", quoting Ihor Dusaniwsky of S3 Partners (investment analysts) in New York.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> The BCMI Cannabis Report<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bnn.ca/video/marijuana-stocks-pull-back-from-peak-is-this-a-concern-for-investors~1029855|title=Video \u2013 BNN \u2013 Business News Network|website=BNN}}</ref> warned that the boom could \"end badly\", with the bubble bursting as other industries' \"manias\" had burst in the past.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-12-14/why-it-s-so-difficult-to-bet-against-canada-s-marijuana-boom|title=Why It's So Hard to Bet Against Canada's Marijuana Boom|date=14 December 2017|via=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref>\n\n====Developments in 2018 and 2019====\nOn 4 January 2018, a plunge in prices was being reported by Bloomberg.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.financialpost.com/investing/pot-stocks-plunge-on-report-that-u-s-is-axing-policy-that-lets-legal-marijuana-flourish|title=Pot stocks plunge as Trump administration moves to weaken marijuana legalization movement|date=4 January 2018}}</ref> An update by [[Forbes]] in mid-July 2018 indicated that year to date, the Canadian Marijuana (stock) Index had declined by 19.1%, but had gained 132% over the previous year.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alanjbrochstein/2018/07/14/canadian-cannabis-stocks-weighed-down-by-capital-raises-and-new-issues/#5f9b42fd4a4a|title=Canadian Cannabis Stocks Weighed Down By Capital Raises And New Issues|date=14 July 2018|magazine=Forbes}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, [[Constellation Brands]] (a beer, wine and spirits producer) announced that it would invest an additional C$5 billion (US$3.8 billion) in Canopy Growth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/cannabis/2018/08/15/constellation-brands-invests-5b-to-boost-stake-in-pot-producer-canopy-growth.html|title=Constellation Brands invests $5B to boost stake in pot producer Canopy Growth|date=15 August 2018|website=thestar.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://business.financialpost.com/cannabis/constellation-brands-spending-5-billion-to-increase-stake-in-canopy-growth|title='This is rocket fuel': Constellation Brands spending $5 billion to boost stake in Canopy Growth|date=15 August 2018}}</ref> After the Constellation deal, the market value of Canopy Growth rose to US$11 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://business.financialpost.com/cannabis/with-5-billion-constellation-deal-canopy-growth-is-emerging-as-the-google-of-pot|title=With $5-billion Constellation deal, Canopy Growth is emerging as the Google of pot|website=Financial Post|accessdate=23 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 September 2018, Tilray Inc. (TLRY:US on NASDAQ) of [[Nanaimo]], a subsidiary or [[Privateer Holdings]], became the world's largest cannabis company in terms of market capitalisation, after a 77% increase in its stock price.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4469273/b-c-based-tilray-becomes-most-valuable-cannabis-company-after-stock-spikes-as-high-as-1600-per-cent/ |title=B.C.-based Tilray becomes most valuable cannabis company after stock spikes as high as 1,600 per cent|publisher=Bloomberg |date=20 September 2018 |accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"auto7\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-09-19/thiel-backed-fund-hits-jackpot-with-12-billion-tilray-stake |title=Peter Thiel-Backed Fund Hits the Jackpot With $12 Billion Tilray Stake|publisher=Bloomberg |date=19 September 2018 |accessdate=20 September 2018}}</ref> However, the share price dropped significantly over the next few days, reducing Tilray's market capitalisation to about US$10 billion compared to the earlier $19+ billion value.<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\nExperts interviewed by [[Global News]] in mid-September continued to warn about market volatility.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4460887/canada-weed-stocks-skyrocketing-investing/ |title=Canadian weed stocks are skyrocketing as legalization looms: But should you invest? |publisher=Global News |date=18 September 2018 |accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nAn October 2019 report stated that cannabis stocks had \"crumbled to their lowest level since 2017\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://business.financialpost.com/cannabis/cannabis-business/cannabis-investing/cannabis-stocks-crumble-to-2017-lows-after-hexo-latest-to-lower-earnings-expectations |title=Cannabis stocks crumble to 2017 lows after Hexo becomes latest to lower earnings expectations |date=10 October 2019 |work=Financial Post|access-date=16 November 2019 |quote=Tilray fell as much 12 per cent, heading for a record low. Canopy slid 9.7 per cent, Aurora lost 5.9 per cent and Cronos Group Inc. fell 6.7 per cent.}}</ref> A report on the market by [[Forbes]] provided this assessment of the situation:<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alanjbrochstein/2019/10/27/cannabis-stocks-now-appeal-to-value-investors/#3878be9d5e8d |title=Cannabis Stocks Now Appeal To Value Investors |date=27 October 2019 |magazine=Forbes |access-date=16 November 2019 |quote=While the capital markets aren\u2019t entirely closed to cannabis companies, the ability to raise equity at reasonable prices has greatly diminished. Investors have responded by sending prices to multi-year lows. The broad sell-off has hit all stocks, but some companies have better balance sheets and operating models than others.}}</ref> <blockquote>2019 has been an extremely disappointing year for investors in cannabis stocks, with the overall market, as measured by the New Cannabis Ventures Global Cannabis Stock Index down 20% after a 55% decline in 2018. The market, which has declined over 71% since early 2018, has moved to three-year lows. The current environment is challenging, as funding has dried up ... Many companies won\u2019t make it or will have to raise capital on extremely unfavorable terms...\"</blockquote>\n\n====Excise tax and sales tax====\n{{Update section|date=September 2018}}\nFrom the early planning stages, the government indicated that the substance would be taxed. An estimate in late 2016 suggested revenues of $618 million per year from a federal tax initially, and eventually, billions, according to a report by Canada's [[Parliamentary Budget Officer]] (PBO).<ref name=\"Cullen\"/> (A recent government estimate indicates that the illegal marijuana industry is worth $7 billion per year.<ref>{{cite news |last=Cryderman |first=Kelley |date=27 November 2016 |title=Report on Canada's marijuana legalization due this week |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/report-on-marijuana-legalization-in-canada-due-this-week/article33065608/ |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |location=Toronto |access-date=2 December 2016}}</ref>) The Task Force report recommended that high-potency cannabis (with a high THC content) be taxed at a higher level than the conventional product to make it less attractive to consumers.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web |url=https://ipolitics.ca/2016/12/13/set-minimum-legal-age-for-marijuana-at-18-says-task-force/ |title=Set minimum legal age for marijuana at 18, says task force |last=Duggan |first=Kyle |date=13 December 2016 |website=iPolitics |publisher=iPolitics |access-date=15 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/federal-task-force-advises-wide-ranging-legalization-of-recreational-marijuana/article33307322/ |title=Federal task force advises wide-ranging legalization of recreational marijuana |last=LeBlanc |first=Daniel |date=13 December 2017 |website=The Globe and Mail |access-date=13 December 2016 |quote=The group of experts, chaired by former Liberal minister Anne McLellan, is also recommending that high-potency products be more heavily taxed, to \"discourage\" their use in the general public.}}</ref>\n\nThe federal government had announced in October 2017 that its budget would include $546 million over five years to prepare the \"legal framework to strictly regulate and restrict access to cannabis\" and another $150 million over six years to enforce the restrictions on drug-impaired driving.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/news/politics/canadas-new-budget-numbers-show-booming-economic-growth-and-booming-spending|title=Canada's new budget numbers show booming economic growth \u2013 and booming spending|date=25 October 2017}}</ref> Health Canada and the Royal Canadian Mounted Police will receive a share of the funds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-26/rolling-out-legal-weed-comes-with-a-high-price-tag-for-canada|title=Rolling Out Legal Weed Comes With a High Price Tag for Canada|date=26 October 2017|via=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref> Of this amount, municipal and indigenous police services should receive $81 million to offset the increased cost of training and resources.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.financialpost.com/commodities/agriculture/ottawa-proposing-legal-weed-tax-of-at-least-1-per-gram-plus-gst|title=Marijuana stocks rally as Ottawa proposes legal weed tax of at least $1 per gram, plus GST|date=10 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 November 2017, the government announced that the federal excise tax, to be shared 50/50 with the provinces and territories, should not exceed $1 a gram or 10 per cent of the producer's price, whichever is higher. The government's press released did not specify higher tax on high-potency products.<ref name=Globe>Mike Hager and Carrie Tait, [https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/british-columbia/provinces-keep-lucrative-online-market-for-legal-marijuana-tothemselves/article37019186/ \"Provinces to keep control of online cannabis sales\"], 18 November 2017.</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> In December 2017, after demands from provinces for a higher percentage, a two-year agreement was signed to provide a full 75% of the tax; as well, the maximum to be taken by the federal government would be $100 million per annum, with any excess paid to the provinces and territories. The final retail price of the product will include provincial sales tax,<ref name=\":0\" /> ranging from 5% to 15% depending on the province.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> This arrangement will be discussed again in December 2018 to determine whether the five months of experience indicated that the 75/25 tax splitting scheme had proved to be appropriate.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Caroline Cahill |title=Finance Ministers Revise Canadian Cannabis Tax Plan |url=http://mjinews.com/finance-ministers-canadian-cannabis-tax-plan/ |website=mjinews.com}}</ref>\n\n== Regulation by province ==\n{{see|Cannabis laws of Canada by province or territory}}\n[[File:2018 British Columbia advertisement of cannabis use.jpg|thumb|Government public service advertisement about the effects of cannabis use in [[Vancouver]].]]\nIn Canada, regulation varies province to province, though there are some general rules regarding promotion, packaging, and advertising. Adult-use cannabis can only be sold in packages of a single colour without graphics other than the logo and a health warning.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2018/06/08/marijuana-industry-seeks-creative-ways-to-brand-product.html|title=Marijuana industry seeks 'creative ways' to brand product|last=Bissett|first=Kevin|date=8 June 2018|work=[[Toronto Star]]|access-date=22 July 2018|agency=[[The Canadian Press]]}}</ref> Cannabis companies in Canada will not be allowed to promote themselves through TV commercials, billboards, or glossy magazine ads, sponsor people or events, or put their names on sports and cultural facilities. To address these advertising challenges, some brands are connecting with popular media influencers like [[Gene Simmons]] and the [[Trailer Park Boys]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/pot-packages|title=Rock stars, actors getting in on Canada's race to legal weed|last=Miller|first=Jacquie|date=3 April 2018|work=[[Ottawa Citizen]]|access-date=22 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Cannabis Act'' (2018) gave provinces the power to determine the method of distribution and sale and whether cannabis use will be legal inside private residence or homes if children are present in the home 12 or more hours in a day,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/business/provincial-marijuana-sales-retail-1.4167735|title=As provinces seek the 'right' price for pot, how it's sold could matter|last=Israel|first=Solomon|date=20 June 2017|work=[[CBC News]]}}</ref> and each will also establish the legal age for cannabis use.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/liberal-legal-marijuana-pot-1.4041902|title=Liberals to announce marijuana will be legal by July 1, 2018|last=Cochrane|first=David|date=26 March 2017|work=[[CBC News]]|access-date=28 March 2017}}</ref> An [[Excise Tax|excise tax]] will be levied, to be shared with the provinces and territories.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/pot-joe-ceci-cannabis-finance-ministers-excise-taxes-1.4443836|title=New cannabis deal an improvement but legal pot won't be a revenue generator, Alberta finance minister predicts|last=Bellefontaine|first=Michelle|date=11 December 2017|work=[[CBC News]]|access-date=}}</ref> According to the federal government, estimated annual sales will be $4 billion (US$3.2b).<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-01-02/taxes-could-help-canada-keep-its-legal-marijuana-prices-in-check|title=Taxes Could Help Canada Keep Its Legal Marijuana Prices in Check|last=Wingrove|first=Josh|date=2 January 2018|work=[[Bloomberg News]]}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Cannabis Act'' (2018) also allows householders to grow up to four cannabis plants, but [[Quebec]] and [[Manitoba]] announced that they would not permit this option.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/3867467/marijuana-legalization-canada-progress/|title=Just months away, here's how pot legalization is shaping up in Canada|last=Paperny|first=Anna Mehler|date=17 November 2017|work=[[Global News]]|access-date=|agency=[[Reuters]]|last2=Saminather|first2=Nichola}}</ref> [[New Brunswick]] is specifying indoor growing only in a separate locked space, but will also allow outdoor growing for plants that are up to 1.52m (5 feet) high.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4238754/quebec-ban-marijuana-home-grows/|title=Why marijuana legalization will likely include bans on home grows|last=Cain|first=Patrick|date=29 May 2018|work=[[Global News]]|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://thehighinvestor.ca/2018/10/02/new-cannabis-regulations-explained-by-province/|title=New Cannabis Regulations Explained \u2013 By Province|date=2 October 2018|work=The High Investor|access-date=7 October 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nMost provinces have set the minimum age to purchase and consume cannabis to 19 years old, although Alberta and Quebec have set it to 18 years old in line with their alcohol and tobacco laws.<ref name=\":3\" /> Manitoba is currently the only province or territory where the legal cannabis age is not identical to the alcohol and tobacco purchase age (19 for cannabis vs. 18 for alcohol/tobacco).<ref>https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/legal-pot-age-19-wrong-message-manitoba-1.4435236</ref>\n\nUnder the newly elected [[Coalition Avenir Qu\u00e9bec]] government, the Deputy Minister for Health in October 2018, [[Lionel Carmant]] announced that the Government will tighten the rules on cannabis consumption, including increasing the legal age to consume to 21 from 18.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/quebec/caq-wants-to-hike-legal-age-for-cannabis-to-21-by-march-minister-says|title=CAQ wants to hike legal age for cannabis to 21 by March, minister says|date=25 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://montreal.ctvnews.ca/cannabis-at-21-quebec-confirms-it-will-raise-age-asap-1.4148095|title=Cannabis at 21: Quebec confirms it will raise age ASAP|date=24 October 2018}}</ref> In 2019, CAQ announced Quebec will also ban the sale of cannabis candies and desserts, including chocolate. because federal cannabis regulations don't go far enough in protecting children from accidentally consuming the drug.<ref>https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/cannabis-regulations-quebec-legal-1.5223723</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/5679335/quebec-to-ban-sale-of-cannabis-candies-in-effort-to-protect-kids/|title=Quebec to ban sale of cannabis candies in effort to protect kids|website=Global News}}</ref>\n\n==Military==\n{{main|Cannabis and the Canadian military}}\nIn early September 2018, the Canadian government released a directive stating that service members will be allowed to use cannabis following legalization in October, but with restrictions on use depending on the individual's duties.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/janetwburns/2018/09/11/canadas-military-green-lights-adult-cannabis-use-for-most-personnel/#2dd92e2875a3|title=Canadian Military Green-Lights Cannabis Use For Most Personnel|first=Janet|last=Burns}}</ref> Per the new regulations, service members may use legal cannabis, but must cease usage:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-canada-cannabis-military/canadas-military-unveils-rules-governing-troop-cannabis-use-idUSKCN1LN29V|title=Canada's military unveils rules governing troop cannabis use|first=Anna Mehler|last=Paperny}}</ref>\n\n* 8 hours prior to duty: all personnel\n* 24 hours prior to duty: anyone operating a weapon or vehicle\n* 28 days before duty: members involved in high-risk activities such as [[high altitude]] parachuting, operating in a [[hyperbaric]] environment, and serving on military aircraft\n*on international operations\n\n==See also==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n* [[Cannabis in Alberta]]\n* [[Cannabis in British Columbia]]\n* [[Cannabis in Manitoba]]\n* [[Cannabis in New Brunswick]]\n* [[Cannabis in Newfoundland and Labrador]]\n* [[Cannabis in the Northwest Territories]]\n* [[Cannabis in Nova Scotia]]\n{{col-break}}\n{{Col-2}}\n{{portal|Canada|Cannabis}}\n* [[Cannabis in Nunavut]]\n* [[Cannabis in Ontario]]\n* [[Cannabis in Prince Edward Island]]\n* [[Cannabis in Quebec]]\n* [[Cannabis in Saskatchewan]]\n* [[Cannabis in Yukon]]\n* [[Cannabis on Canadian Indian reserves]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last1 = Nolin |first1 = Pierre Claude|last2= Kenny|first2=Colin |year =2003 |title =Cannabis: Report of the Senate Special Committee on Illegal Drugs\n |url =https://books.google.com/books?id=L_5gu-eUfE8C&pg=PP1#v=twopage&q&f=true |publisher= University of Toronto Press |isbn=0-8020-8946-1}}\n* {{cite book|author=Kyle Grayson|title=Chasing Dragons: Security, Identity, and Illicit Drugs in Canada|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KUQHs7XNZ2AC&pg=PP1#v=twopage&q&f=true |date=12 April 2008|publisher=University of Toronto Press|isbn=978-0-8020-9479-7}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.ccsa.ca/Resource%20Library/CCSA-Canadian-Drug-Summary-Cannabis-2018-en.pdf|publisher=Canadian Centre on Substance Use and Addiction |title=Cannabis (Canadian Drug Summary) |date=June 2018}}\n*Ryan Macdonald; Michelle Rotermann, ( 2017) {{cite book|url=https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/n1/pub/11-626-x/11-626-x2017077-eng.htm|title=Experimental Estimates of Cannabis Consumption in Canada, 1960 to 2015 |publisher=Statistics Canada \u2013 Economic Analysis Division and Health Analysis Division}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Cannabis in Canada}}\n* [http://www.parl.gc.ca/common/Committee_SenHome.asp?Language=E&Parl=37&Ses=1&comm_id=85 2002 Canadian Senate Special Committee on Illicit Drugs]\n* [http://www2.parl.gc.ca/HousePublications/Publication.aspx?pub=bill&doc=C-38&parl=37&ses=2&language=E Failed decriminalization bill]\n* [http: