igital since April 11, 2008 on [[Ultra high frequency|UHF]] channel 22.<ref>http://digitalhome.ca/forum/showthread.php?t=84662 \" Global (Vancouver) Now Testing Digital OTA Channel 22.2, ''Digital Home Canada'', April 11, 2008</ref> On June 29, 2011, CHAN-DT increased its effective radiated power (ERP) from 8.3&nbsp;kW to its post-transitional allotment of 40&nbsp;kW. CHAN's primary Vancouver transmitter was the station's only one required to go digital by the transition deadline. Shaw Media has committed to converting all of the other over-the-air transmitters to digital by 2016.\n\nCHAN shut down its analogue signal, over [[Very high frequency|VHF]] channel 8, on August 31, 2011, the official date in which Canadian television stations in CRTC-designated mandatory markets [[Digital television in Canada|transitioned from analogue to digital broadcasts]]. The station's digital signal remained on its pre-transition UHF channel 22.<ref name=\"Analog to Digital\">[http://digitaltv.gc.ca/eng/1298734754616/1298734754746 Digital Television \u2013 Office of Consumer Affairs (OCA)<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131119235800/http://digitaltv.gc.ca/eng/1298734754616/1298734754746|date=2013-11-19}}</ref><ref name=\"YouTube video of transition\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EoF7jVAgg2g</ref> Through the use of [[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]], digital television receivers display CHAN-DT's [[virtual channel]] as its analogue-era VHF channel 8. The station's electronic program guide began functioning properly on January 28, 2012.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://globalnews.ca/bc/ Global BC]\n*[https://www.corusent.com/ Corus Entertainment corporate website]\n*[http://www.broadcasting-history.ca/listing_and_histories/television/chan-dt Canadian Communications Foundation \u2013 CHAN-DT History]\n*[http://www3.telus.net/vanradiomuseum/BCTVGallery.html Vancouver Radio Museum \u2013 CHAN-TV/BCTV]\n*{{RecnetCanada|CHAN-DT}}\n*{{TV Fool|CHAN-DT}}\n\n{{British Columbia TV}}\n{{Global TV}}\n{{Corus Entertainment}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chan-Dt}}\n[[Category:Burnaby]]\n[[Category:Global Television Network stations|HAN-DT]]\n[[Category:Corus Entertainment]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1960]]\n[[Category:Television stations in Vancouver|HAN-DT]]\n[[Category:1960 establishments in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League over-the-air television broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Vancouver Canucks broadcasters]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Global TV station in Vancouver}}\n{{redirect|BCTV|the former Boston Catholic Television|CatholicTV}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox broadcast\n| call_letters             = CHAN-DT\n| city                     = \n| station_logo             = Globalbc.svg\n| logo_size                = 210px\n| station_branding         = Global BC ''(general)''<br>''[[Global News]]'' ''(newscasts)''\n| station_slogan           = ''We are BC's news.''\n| digital                  = 22 ([[ultra high frequency|UHF]])\n| virtual                  = 8.1 ([[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]])\n| subchannels              = \n| other_chs                = [[#Transmitters|See below]]\n| affiliations             = '''8.1:''' [[Global Television Network|Global]] ('''[[Owned-and-operated station|O&O]]'''; 2001\u2013present)\n| owner                    = [[Corus Entertainment]]\n| licensee                 = Corus Television [[limited partnership|Limited Partnership]]<ref>[https://crtc.gc.ca/ownership/eng/cht032h.pdf Ownership Chart 32H \u2013 CORUS \u2013 TV & Discretionary Services]</ref>\n| location                 = [[Vancouver|Vancouver, British Columbia]]\n| country                  = Canada\n| airdate                  = {{Start date and age|1960|10|31|p=y}}\n| enddate                  = \n| callsign_meaning         = '''CHAN'''nel\n| sister_stations          = '''TV:''' [[Global News: BC 1]], [[CHBC-DT]]<br>'''Radio:''' [[CKNW]], [[CHMJ]], [[CFOX-FM]], [[CFMI-FM]]\n| former_callsigns         = CHAN-TV (1960\u20132011)\n| former_channel_numbers   = '''Analog:'''<br> 8 ([[very high frequency|VHF]], 1960\u20132011)\n| former_affiliations      = [[Independent station (North America)|Independent]] (1960\u20131961)<br>[[CTV Television Network|CTV]] (1961\u20132001)\n| effective_radiated_power = 40 [[watt|kW]]\n| HAAT                     = {{convert|656|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| facility_id              = \n| coordinates              = {{coord|49|21|26|N|122|57|13|W|type:landmark}}\n| licensing_authority      = [[Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission|CRTC]]\n| homepage                 = {{URL|https://globalnews.ca/bc/|Global BC}}\n}}\n\n'''CHAN-DT''', [[virtual channel]] 8 ([[Ultra high frequency|UHF]] [[digital terrestrial television|digital]] channel 22), is a [[Global Television Network|Global]] [[owned-and-operated station|owned-and-operated]] [[television station]] [[city of license|licensed]] to [[Vancouver|Vancouver, British Columbia]], Canada, serving as the network's West Coast [[Flagship (broadcasting)|flagship]] outlet. The station is owned by [[Corus Entertainment]]. CHAN-DT's studios are located on Enterprise Street in the suburban city of [[Burnaby]], which also houses Global's national news centre. The station's transmitter is located atop [[Mount Seymour]].\n\nOn [[cable television|cable]], CHAN-DT is available on [[Shaw Communications|Shaw Cable]] channel 11. On [[satellite television|satellite]], the station is carried on [[Bell TV]] channel 252, [[Shaw Direct]] channels 336 (Classic) and 5 (Advanced), and [[Rogers Cable|Rogers Personal TV]] channel 119. There is also a high-definition feed on Shaw Cable [[digital cable|digital]] channel 211, and Shaw Direct channels 2 (Classic) and 502 (Advanced). The station is available throughout British Columbia through a large network of [[broadcast relay station#translator stations|rebroadcasters]].\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Chan8.png|thumb|left|165px|CHAN's original logo, used until 1963.]]\n[[File:Chan-chek.png|thumb|right|200px|CHAN-TV and CHEK-TV shared this logo in the 1960s; it was often used when the stations simulcasted programming.]]\nThe station first signed on the air at 4:45 p.m. on October 31, 1960. Founded by Vantel Broadcasting, it originally operated as an [[Independent station (North America)|independent station]].<ref name=\"vrm\">[http://www3.telus.net/vanradiomuseum/BCTVGallery.html CHAN TV/BCTV/GLOBAL B.C. GALLERY CH. 8/CABLE 11 IN VANCOUVER]</ref> It acquired several programs from [[CTV Television Network|CTV]] upon that network's launch on October 1, 1961; it would eventually join the network formally in 1965.<ref>Gittins, Susan (1999). CTV: The Television Wars. Toronto: Stoddart Publishing Co. Ltd. {{ISBN|0-7737-3125-3}}.</ref> The station operated from a temporary studio housed at 1219 Richards Street in [[Downtown Vancouver]], until its full-time studio facility at 7850 Enterprise Street in Burnaby was opened in 1962<ref>[http://www.broadcasting-history.ca/listing_and_histories/television/chan-dt]</ref> Soon after the station's launch, CHAN began installing relay transmitters across the province, and now reaches 96% of British Columbia. Through its over-the-air signal, CHAN also reaches an American audience in neighbouring [[Whatcom County, Washington]].\n\n[[Image:BCTV 1970s Logo.png|165px|thumb|left|BCTV's iconic original logo, used for more than 20 years from 1973\u20131994. The logo featured the [[pacific dogwood]] flower, the [[List of Canadian provincial and territorial symbols|provincial flower]] of British Columbia.<ref>[http://www3.telus.net/vanradiomuseum/bctv_dogwood.jpg]</ref>]]\nIn 1963, local entrepreneur [[Frank Griffiths]], owner of radio station [[CKNW]] (980 AM), purchased CHAN-TV from Vantel, along with nearby [[CBC Television|CBC]] affiliate [[CHEK-DT|CHEK-TV]] (channel 6) in the [[Vancouver Island]] city of [[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria]], from its original owner, David Armstrong. At that point, CHEK began airing a few CTV programs, usually scheduled at different times than when CHAN aired them. It would become a full-time CTV affiliate in January 1981, but maintained a shuffled schedule. Griffiths' Western Broadcasting Communications later sold a minority share of the station to [[Selkirk Communications]], before buying back full control in 1989.\n\nIn 1986, BCTV set up a fully functional broadcast studio [[Expo 86#Corporations and Non-Governmental Organizations|pavilion]] at the Vancouver [[Expo 86]], whose theme was transportation and communication. The BCTV pavilion allowed visitors to see, and participate, in every step of how a television station operates, as well as how newscasts and television shows were produced. The pavilion was also used by the station for coverage of the Expo, and by visiting journalists.<ref>http://bobbea.com/expo-86/bctv.html</ref><ref>http://www.bharch.ca/projects/cat/36/id/145</ref><ref>http://www.vancouverisawesome.com/2014/05/08/archie-goes-to-expo-86-the-full-comic-book-online-cc-sarahsaysstuff/</ref><ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=WaUJAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA110&lpg=PA110&dq=expo+86+BCTV+pavilion#v=onepage&q=expo%2086%20BCTV%20pavilion&f=false | title=Vancouver's Expo '86| isbn=9781439642597| last1=Cotter| first1=Bill| date=2009-11-30}}</ref>\n\nAs early as 1971, CHAN unofficially began using the brand \"BCTV\".<ref>[http://www.bharch.ca/projects/cat/36/id/145]</ref><ref>[http://bobbea.com/expo-86/bctv.html]</ref> In 1973, BCTV became CHAN's official on-air branding, which remained in use until 2001, when it adopted the \"Global BC\" brand. The \"BCTV\" brand was retained for its local newscasts until February 2006. However, the \"BCTV\" brand became so firmly established in the province that many people still call the station by that name today.\n\n===Hostility to CTV===\nCHAN was CTV's third-largest affiliate, and by far the largest in [[Western Canada]]. As such, it was one of the backbones of the CTV network for many years and one of the network's most successful affiliates. However, it was always somewhat hostile toward CTV. Management believed that the network's flagship station, [[CFTO-DT|CFTO-TV]] in [[Toronto]], had too much influence over the network. In particular, CHAN felt CFTO received favouritism in the production of CTV's Canadian programming in the late 1960s and early 1970s.\n\n[[Image:BCTV 1990's Logo.svg|thumb|right|150px|CHAN's final \"BCTV\" logo. The stylized pacific dogwood was modernized in 1994 and was used until the affiliation switch on August 31, 2001.<ref>[http://hinto.tripod.com/newswatch/yvr-tv/station.html tv vancouver: station overview]</ref>]]\nNonetheless, until 1997, CHAN bought the provincial rights to several popular series from CFTO's parent company, [[Baton Broadcast System|Baton Broadcasting]]. However, tensions were exacerbated that year when Baton won a licence to operate a new television station in Vancouver, [[CIVT-DT|CIVT-TV]] (channel 32), and immediately moved much of CHAN's stronger programs there. Baton won controlling interest in CTV soon after channel 32's launch, and it became an open secret that CIVT would eventually replace CHAN as the CTV station for the Vancouver [[Media market|market]]. CHAN had signed a long-term contract with CTV several years earlier that would not expire until 1999, but was extended to 2001. However, outside of the 40 hours of programming per week that this allowed for, and CHAN's own local news programs, the station had to rely on lower-profile programming supplied by parent company Western International Communications. A small amount of [[CHUM Limited]]-produced programs also aired on CHAN at times during the period from 1997 to 2001, including ''[[CityLine]]''.\n\n===The affiliation shakeup of 2001===\n{{main|2001 Vancouver TV realignment}}\nOn June 6, 2000<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20010125022000/http://vancouver.globaltv.com/bc/insidebctv/station/stories/station-20000928-171754.html]</ref> WIC's stations were purchased by [[Canwest|Canwest Global Communications]], which owned the [[Global Television Network]]. As a result, CHAN was due to become the Global outlet for all of British Columbia. Although Global already owned a station in Vancouver, [[CKVU-DT|CKVU]] (channel 10), it opted to sell CKVU to CHUM Limited and move its affiliation to CHAN, evidently due to that station's significantly higher coverage and local news viewership. CHAN-TV's affiliation agreement with CTV expired on September 1, 2001, sparking a major shakeup in British Columbia television:\n*The CTV affiliation, jointly held by CHAN and sister station CHEK, moved to CIVT, which became a CTV O&O station that branded for a short time as \"BC CTV\" (later revised to \"CTV British Columbia\"). Both switches left CTV dependent on cable and satellite coverage to reach the rest of the province, as CTV has refused to set up rebroadcasters in the rest of the province. CHAN retained the rights to ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'', which was carried by CTV in all of its other O&O markets, until the talk show ended its run in [[2011 in American television|2011]].\n*The Global affiliation, held by CKVU, moved to CHAN, which became the network's new O&O under the \"Global BC\" brand. CKVU meanwhile adopted the \"ckvu13\" brand and briefly became an independent station carrying CHUM-supplied programming, some of which had aired the previous season on [[KVOS-TV]] (channel 12) in [[Bellingham, Washington]]. The station became a [[Citytv]] owned-and-operated station (the eventual [[television system]]-turned-network's first expansion outside of Toronto) several months later, after the sale to CHUM was approved.\n*Most of CHAN's former WIC-supplied programming, which migrated to Canwest's newly launched [[E! (Canadian TV system)|CH]] system, moved to CHEK (where other WIC programs already aired). The station was rebranded \"CH Vancouver Island\"; it was later renamed ''CHEK News'' in 2007 as part of CH's rebranding to E! and to simply \"CHEK\" in 2009 following the demise of the E! system.\n*Religious station [[CHNU-DT|CHNU]] (channel 10; later a [[Joytv]] station, now an independent station), launched two weeks later, and a CHUM-owned [[CTV Two|NewNet]] station in Victoria, [[CIVI-DT|CIVI]] (channel 53), launched just over two weeks after that.\n\n==Programming==\nFor the most part, CHAN does not deviate much from the Global schedule. Some programs carried on Global's daytime schedule in other markets \u2013 primarily library programs from Corus Entertainment's specialty channels \u2013 are not cleared on CHAN in order to make room for the station's various local news programs.\n\nIn February, the station broadcasts the annual [[Variety, the Children's Charity|Variety]] ''Show of Hearts'' [[telethon]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abbynews.com/community/abbotsford-girl-to-appear-on-variety-show-of-hearts-telethon/|title=Abbotsford girl to appear on Variety Show of Hearts Telethon|last=Community|date=2019-02-07|website=Abbotsford News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-18}}</ref>\n\n===Selected former non-network programs===\n* ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]'', aired weeknights at 12:37 a.m. from February 1994 to August 1995\n* ''280-JOCK'' followed ''News Hour Final'' at 12:05 a.m. until it was cancelled in late 1994, which pushed back ''Late Show'' to 12:37 a.m. for several months.\n* ''[[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno]]'', aired weeknights at 12:07&nbsp;a.m. from August 1995 to August 2001\n:As [[CHUM Limited]] held the rights to this program throughout the rest of the country, when [[CIVI-DT|CIVI-TV]] launched in nearby [[Victoria, British Columbia]], the broadcast rights transferred over to that station.\n* ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'' (1986\u20132011) aired at 4:00&nbsp;p.m. on CHAN because the station owned the provincial television rights to this show, dating back to its days as a CTV affiliate. In every other market in which CTV owned a station, that network owned the local rights to ''Oprah''.\n* ''[[The Bold and the Beautiful]]'' aired weekdays at 2:00 p.m. [[CTV Television Network|CTV]] from 1995 to 2001.\n\n==News operation==\n[[File:Global Vancouver News Hour (Vancouver 2010).jpg|thumb|right|250px|Global BC ''News Hour'' during the [[2010 Winter Olympics]].]]\n[[File:Global BC van.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Global BC's microwave ENG vans.]]\nCHAN-DT presently broadcasts 47\u00bd hours of locally produced newscasts each week (with 7\u00bd hours on weekdays and 5 hours on Saturdays and Sundays); in regards to the number of hours devoted to news programming, it is the highest local newscast output among Global's television stations (either owned-and-operated or affiliated), as well as among all Canadian television stations (after the drastic reduction of [[Hamilton, Ontario]]'s [[CHCH-DT]] total weekly news programming due to budget cuts in December 2015). The station's Burnaby studios also serve as the production facilities for Global's Vancouver-based English national evening newscast ''[[Global National]]'' and the [[Shaw Multicultural Channel]] [[Standard Chinese|Mandarin]] national evening newscast ''Global National Mandarin'' (2012\u20132016). Unlike most Global stations that carry midday newscasts, CHAN airs its noon newscast seven days a week. The station's newscast schedule is very similar to that of an affiliate of the [[Big Three television networks]] ([[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], [[CBS]] and [[NBC]]) in the United States, although as Global lacks a national morning news program, CHAN's weekday morning newscast runs a length similar to that of many [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] and other news-producing non-Big Three U.S. stations.\n\nCHAN's news operation is well respected in the industry. Ever since the station first aired an hour-long newscast in the 1960s, a major part of the station's cash flow has gone into its news department, and it has garnered high ratings and major awards since then. The station's 6:00 p.m. ''[[News Hour (Canadian news program)|News Hour]]'' broadcast has been the highest-rated local [[newscast]] in the province for many years, as well as the most-watched in all of Canada.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://vancouversun.com/news/Parsons+leave+Global+News+Hour+earlier+than+expected/2346590/story.html |title=Parsons to leave Global's News Hour earlier than expected \u2013 Vancouver Sun |access-date=2009-12-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091220034105/http://www.vancouversun.com/news/Parsons+leave+Global+News+Hour+earlier+than+expected/2346590/story.html |archive-date=2009-12-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The station's on-air news style was even used as an inspiration for [[Ted Turner]]'s [[CNN]], as both use the newsroom as a backdrop during the broadcast. The current newsroom was constructed in 1975; it was rebuilt in the early 1990s, moving the studio out of the newsroom, but keeping it as a backdrop, and was later remodeled in 2001 and 2006.\n\nStarting in the early 1990s, CHAN harboured ambitions of producing an early evening national newscast from its studios. In fact, several newscast pilots were produced at CHAN, suggesting the network was seriously considering such a move. However, that newscast never materialized; instead, CHAN began producing ''[[Canada Tonight]]'', which aired on most WIC-owned stations beginning in 1993. Two versions were produced: one for British Columbia itself, hosted by CKNW radio commentator [[Bill Good]] (who later went to CTV's current Vancouver O&O station, CIVT-TV, and retired in December 2010) and a national version, hosted by [[Tony Parsons (Canadian journalist)|Tony Parsons]], who also anchored CHAN's nightly news program, the ''News Hour''. When Canwest purchased CHAN, the stories that were once sourced from CTV's other affiliates throughout the country were replaced by stories sourced from Global's affiliates.\n\nFrom 2001, when the station became \"Global BC\", the news department underwent a minor retitling as ''BCTV News on Global''. CHAN opted to keep the \"BCTV\" name for its newscasts, since that brand was still very well respected in the province; it also wanted to keep CIVT from using the name itself, as it contained the letters \"CTV.\" In addition, CHAN became the headquarters for Global's national news centre and the production facility for a new national newscast, ''Global National'' (which is currently anchored by former CTV and NBC correspondent [[Dawna Friesen]] on weeknights and on weekends by Robin Gill;<ref>http://globalnews.ca/bc/programme/weekend-news-hour-bc/personalities/{{dead link|date=January 2018|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> originally anchored beforehand by [[Kevin Newman (Canadian journalist)|Kevin Newman]]), thus fulfilling its longstanding dream of producing a national newscast. The program is broadcast live-to-tape from Vancouver at 5:30 p.m. ([[Pacific Time Zone]]), airing locally prior to the 6:00&nbsp;p.m. ''News Hour'' broadcast.\n\nThe \"BCTV\" brand was finally discontinued when Global introduced its new logo and on-air identity on February 6, 2006; CHAN's newscasts were rebranded as ''Global News'' (with its overall branding changing to \"Global BC\") at this point. In 2006, Global struck an agreement with the Canadian Traffic Network to supply the station with a [[Robinson R44]] news [[helicopter]] with gyroscopic camera mounts. The helicopter is branded as \"Global 1\" \u2013 the same designation used for the news helicopters used by other Global stations \u2013 which is shared with CKNW, and is the second news helicopter in Vancouver (after that used by CIVT).{{Ref|http://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&ct=res&cd=1&url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.canada.com%2Fvancouversun%2Fnews%2Fwestcoastnews%2Fstory.html%3Fid%3D0a1dbbb3-1adc-44ae-9985-6ee68b7ef9b1&ei=jcE8RfufN47-gwPeucmjBA&sig=__3JiUocgdd8Of27JWdbli78VCQPo=&sig2=Nji6pXM3skwBP5TNe95Pvg}}\n\nOn December 16, 2009, Tony Parsons anchored his final newscast at CHAN after 34 years as anchor of the ''News Hour''.<ref>[https://archive.is/20091217091630/http://www.vancouversun.com/Tony+Parsons+Global+News+part+ways/2344638/story.html Tony Parsons and Global News part ways \u2013 Vancouver Sun]</ref> It was expected that he would remain until after the [[2010 Winter Olympics]], but left much earlier than expected for unknown reasons. Parsons joined CHEK as anchor of its 10:00&nbsp;p.m. newscast on March 15, 2010 and also began anchoring the evening newscasts at CBC Television O&O [[CBUT-DT|CBUT]] (channel 2) on April 12, 2010, remaining at both stations until his retirement in 2013.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.timescolonist.com/Legendary+broadcaster+Tony+Parsons+makes+debut+Island+anchor+Monday/2679635/story.html |title=Legendary broadcaster Tony Parsons makes his debut as an Island anchor Monday \u2013 Times Colonist |access-date=2010-03-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100322233053/http://www.timescolonist.com/Legendary+broadcaster+Tony+Parsons+makes+debut+Island+anchor+Monday/2679635/story.html |archive-date=2010-03-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/tony-parsons-joins-cbc-news-vancouver-1.947199 Tony Parsons joins CBC News Vancouver]</ref>\n\nCHAN began broadcasting its local newscasts in [[High-definition television|high definition]] on September 20, 2010 (Dawna Friesen was named anchor of ''Global National'' on that same date); the station debuted a new graphics package as well as an HD-ready virtual set two weeks later on October 4, which utilized the same set with minor changes to the desk. CHAN-DT uses [[Betacam SP]] analogue videotape for all of its local advertisements and for pre-recorded segments within its newscasts; however, the station is slowly moving to a digital format for video production. [[MPEG-2]] transmission is used on nearly all non-local broadcasts.\n\nOn January 11, 2012, Shaw Media filed a license application with the [[Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission]] (CRTC) \u2013 which was approved on July 20, 2012 \u2013 to launch a [[Category B services|Category B]] [[Digital cable|digital-only]] [[specialty channel|specialty service]] that would serve as a British Columbia-focused news channel operated by CHAN-DT and utilizing its news staff.<ref>[http://www.broadcastermagazine.com/news/shaw-media-to-launch-all-news-network-in-bc/1000817210/ Shaw Media to Launch All-News Network in BC] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120122024319/http://www.broadcastermagazine.com/news/shaw-media-to-launch-all-news-network-in-bc/1000817210/ |date=2012-01-22 }}, ''Broadcaster Magazine'', January 11, 2012.</ref> The channel, which was given the name [[Global News: BC 1]], launched on March 14, 2013. It became the fourth regional news channel in Canada and the first outside of Ontario (joining Toronto-based 24-hour services [[CP24]] and the now-defunct [[CityNews Channel|City''News Channel'']], and Hamilton-based independent station \u2013 and former CHAN sister station under their prior Canwest ownership \u2013 CHCH-DT, which carries a heavy local newscast schedule along with some entertainment programming).<ref>[http://www.globaltvbc.com/shaw+granted+24-hour+all-news+channel+for+british+columbia/6442683116/story.html Shaw granted 24-hour all-news channel for British Columbia], ''Global News'', July 20, 2012</ref>\n\nOn August 27, 2012, CHAN-DT expanded its weekday morning newscast to four hours, with the addition of a half-hour at 5:00 a.m. (making it only the second Canadian station with a pre-5:30 a.m. morning newscast, after CHCH-DT), the 5:00 to 6:00 a.m. hour of the newscast was re-titled as the ''Early Morning News''; in addition on September 2, 2012, the station also expanded its Sunday morning newscast to three hours with the addition of an hour at 7:00 a.m. The expansions of CHAN's morning newscasts were part of a benefits package that was included as a condition of the sale of the Global Television Network to Shaw Communications.<ref>[http://www.broadcastermagazine.com/news/global-news-boosts-local-programming-across-the-country/1001418952/ Global News Boosts Local Programming Across the Country] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140107031528/http://www.broadcastermagazine.com/news/global-news-boosts-local-programming-across-the-country/1001418952/ |date=2014-01-07 }}, ''Broadcaster Magazine'', May 30, 2012.</ref>\n\n=== Current Local News Programs<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://globalnews.ca/bc/programs/|title=Programs {{!}} Global BC News|website=Global News|access-date=2016-07-18}}</ref> ===\n* ''[[Morning News (Canadian TV series)|Global News Morning]]'' \u2013 airing from 5:00\u20139:00 a.m. PT weekdays and 7:00\u201310:00 a.m. weekends. Until April 2016, the program was titled ''Morning News'' (''Early Morning News'' from 5-6am and ''Saturday/Sunday Morning News'' on Saturday and Sunday, respectively). It is hosted by Sonia Sunger and Paul Haysom with Mark Madryga on weather, Kaitlyn Herbst doing in-studio traffic and Amber Belzer in Global 1 for airborne traffic. ''Global News Morning'' on Global BC is BC's most-watched morning program. On October 7, 2016, long-time anchor Steve Darling announced that his job had been eliminated and he no longer works for Global BC.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/stevedarling/status/784489838158368768|title=steve darling on Twitter|newspaper=Twitter|access-date=2016-10-12}}</ref> On weekends, it is anchored by Lynn Colliar, Kasia Bodurka with weather and Jay Janower with sports.\n* ''Global News at Noon'' \u2013 airing daily from 12:00\u20131:00 p.m. PT. On weekdays, ''Global News at Noon'' is anchored by Sonia Sunger and Paul Haysom with Mark Madryga on weather. On weekends, it is anchored by Lynn Colliar with Kasia Bodurka on weather and Jay Janower on sports. The program was titled ''Noon News Hour'' before April 2016. Global BC is the only Global station to air a noon newscast on the weekends.\n* ''Global News at 5'' \u2013 airing from 5:00\u20135:30 p.m. PT weekdays, before ''[[Global National]]''. It is anchored by Sophie Lui with Kristi Gordon on weather. There is no sports on this newscast. Squire Barnes does Plays of the Week on Mondays. Before April 2016, the program was titled ''Early News''.\n* [[News Hour (Canadian news program)|''Global News Hour at 6'']] \u2013 airing daily from 6:00\u20137:00 pm PT. On weekdays, ''Global News Hour at 6'' is anchored by Chris Gailus and Sophie Lui with Kristi Gordon on weather and Squire Barnes on sports. On weekends, ''Global News Hour at 6'' is anchored by Sonia Deol with Yvonne Schalle on weather and Barry Deley with sports. ''Global News Hour at 6'' was previously called ''News Hour'' before April 2016.\n* ''Global News at 11'' \u2013 airing daily from 11:00\u201311:35 p.m. PT. It is anchored by Jay Durant and Anne Drewa on weeknights with Kristi Gordon on weather. On weekends, it is anchored by Jordan Armstrong with Yvonne Schalle on weather and Barry Deley with sports. Until fall 2015, the weeknight edition of ''Global News at 11'' (then called ''News Hour Final'') was a full hour long from 11 p.m.-12 a.m. However, it was shortened to accommodate airing ''[[The Late Show with Stephen Colbert]]'' at 11:35 p.m. Before April 2016, ''Global News at 10'' was titled ''News Hour Final'' on weekdays and ''News Final'' on weekends. On [[Global News: BC 1|BC1]], an hour-long edition of ''Global News at 11'' is aired, titled ''Global News at 10'', from 10:00\u201311:00 p.m. (10:00\u201310:30 pm on weekends).\n\n===Notable current on-air staff===\n* [[Jill Krop]] \u2013 Global BC Station Manager\n* [[Chris Gailus]] \u2013 Global News Hour at 6 co-anchor (weekdays)\n* [[Dawna Friesen]] \u2013 (2010\u2013present); anchor of ''[[Global National]]''\n* [[Robin Gill (journalist)|Robin Gill]] \u2013 (Sunday 2008\u2013present and Saturday 2011\u2013present) anchor of ''[[Global National]]''\n\n===Notable former on-air staff===\n* [[Jennifer Burke]] (1991\u201398); now at [[CTV News Channel (Canada)|CTV News Channel]]\n* [[Deborra Hope]] (1981\u2013 March 27, 2014)\n* [[Bill Good|Bill Good Jr.]] (1993\u20132001); was co-anchor at [[CIVT-DT|CTV Vancouver]] from 2001 to 2010, retired at [[CKNW]] in 2014\n* [[Frank Griffiths]] (1963\u201394)\n* [[Rena Heer]] (2005\u201307); was at [[CIVT-DT]] in Vancouver\n* [[Mi-Jung Lee]] (1992\u201398); now at [[CIVT-DT]] in Vancouver\n* [[Pamela Martin (television reporter)|Pamela Martin]] (1977\u20132001); was Director of Engagement for Premier [[Christy Clark]] & Liaison to the Leader of the [[British Columbia Liberal Party|British Columbia Liberal]]\n* [[Tara Nelson]] (February 26, 2005\u20132008); now at [[CFCN-DT]] in Calgary\n* [[Kevin Newman (Canadian journalist)|Kevin Newman]] (2001\u201308); served as Ottawa-based anchor of ''[[Global National]]'' from 2008 to 2010, now with [[CTV News]]\n* [[Harvey Oberfeld]] (1979\u20132006)\n* [[Tony Parsons (Canadian journalist)|Tony Parsons]] \u2013 ''News Hour'' anchor (1975\u20132009) later anchor at [[CHEK-DT]] and [[CBUT-DT]] from 2010 to 2013\n* [[Jack Webster (journalist)|Jack Webster]] (1978\u201387)\n\n==Transmitters==\nCHAN operates the single largest private transmitter network in [[North America]], with roughly one hundred transmitters (some of which are community-owned) providing over-the-air coverage to 97% of British Columbia. Therefore, the network relies exclusively on cable and satellite in the municipalities not covered by the transmitter network (including most where [[CFCN-DT|CFCN]] in [[Calgary]] and [[CFRN-DT|CFRN]] in [[Edmonton]] were already available over-the-air prior to 2001).\n{{kml}}\n\n===Owned-and-operated transmitters===\n'''''[[Broadcast relay station#Semi-satellites|semi-satellite]]s are displayed in bold italics.'''''<br>\nNote that the transmitters in [[Kelowna]] and the surrounding area (CHKL-TV) are ''in addition'' to [[CHBC-DT]], a co-owned separate Global station in Kelowna that originates its own local evening newscasts, but which carries Global BC's programming at virtually all other times. CHAN is the last owned-and-operated station of the three major Canadian broadcast networks (CBC, CTV and Global) in the Vancouver market to still operate rebroadcasters throughout most of the province.\n\n====Analogue-to-digital conversion====\nOn October 15, 2012, CHAN-DT's transmitters in Kelowna, Penticton and Vernon were converted to digital signals.<ref>[https://community.shaw.ca/servlet/JiveServlet/download/1348-5-2863/FAQ%27s%20for%20Digital%20Transition.pdf SHAW IS UPGRADING ITS OVER-THE-AIR TELEVISION TO DIGITAL]</ref> These were the station's first rebroadcast transmitters to be converted to digital as part of Shaw's efforts to convert all of its television transmitters to digital by 2016.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Station\n! [[City of license]]\n! [[channel (broadcasting)|Channel]]\n! [[Effective radiated power|ERP]]\n! [[height above average terrain|HAAT]]\n!Transmitter coordinates\n|- \n| '''CHKL-DT'''\n| [[Kelowna]]\n| 24 ([[ultra high frequency|UHF]])\n| 31.2&nbsp;kW\n| 509.6 m\n| {{coord|49|58|2|N|119|31|50|W|type:landmark|name=CHKL-DT}}\n|- \n| '''CHKL-DT-1'''\n| [[Penticton]]\n| 30 (UHF)\n| 3&nbsp;kW\n| 365.3 m\n| {{coord|49|39|34|N|119|34|22|W|type:landmark|name=CHKL-DT-1}}\n|- \n| '''CHKL-DT-2'''\n| [[Vernon, British Columbia|Vernon]]\n| 22 (UHF)\n| 3&nbsp;kW\n| 184.6 m\n| {{coord|50|16|58|N|119|19|13|W|type:landmark|name=CHKL-DT-2}}\n|- \n| '''CHKM-DT'''\n| [[Kamloops]]\n| 22 (UHF)\n| 30&nbsp;kW\n| 152.7 m\n| {{coord|50|40|9|N|120|23|52|W|type:landmark|name=CHKM-TV}}\n|- \n| '''CIFG-DT'''\n| [[Prince George, British Columbia|Prince George]]\n| 29 (UHF)\n| 30&nbsp;kW\n| 482 m\n| {{coord|53|54|48|N|122|27|15|W|type:landmark|name=CIFG-DT}}\n|- 